00:04:57.920 --> 00:05:00.820
to synthesize the genetic
sequence with our ability

00:05:00.820 --> 00:05:03.910
to read genetic sequence and
compare that to something

00:05:03.910 --> 00:05:04.880
called "Moore's law."

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:06.713
You guys have probably
heard of Moore's law.

00:05:06.713 --> 00:05:11.080
It's the speed with which
computers increase in speed.

00:05:11.080 --> 00:05:12.780
So this is a log scale.

00:05:12.780 --> 00:05:15.280
And this, here, is how
computers increase in speeds.

00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:18.760
So you can see it's basically
linear in log scale.

00:05:18.760 --> 00:05:20.111
And sequencing looks like this.

00:05:20.111 --> 00:05:22.610
It kind of follows Moore's law,
and then next-gen sequencing

00:05:22.610 --> 00:05:24.670
comes around, and just explodes.

00:05:24.670 --> 00:05:25.260
Right?

00:05:25.260 --> 00:05:27.850
Suddenly we're able
to read whole genomes.

00:05:27.850 --> 00:05:28.990
It's relatively trivial.

00:05:28.990 --> 00:05:30.350
We have a MiSeq in the lab.

00:05:30.350 --> 00:05:34.005
Those things-- I mean, they
run 20 million bases at a time,

00:05:34.005 --> 00:05:36.530
and it takes eight hours to
run one of those experiments.

00:05:36.530 --> 00:05:37.030
OK?

00:05:37.030 --> 00:05:38.910
So it's huge amounts of data.

00:05:38.910 --> 00:05:41.180
It's really exciting to
have that capability.

00:05:41.180 --> 00:05:44.290
And this is kind of where
synthesizing DNA goes.

00:05:44.290 --> 00:05:45.436
OK?

00:05:45.436 --> 00:05:47.060
The next important
part of the equation

00:05:47.060 --> 00:05:49.280
is how cheap
sequencing has gotten.

00:05:49.280 --> 00:05:51.390
So this is the cost
of DNA sequencing.

00:05:51.390 --> 00:05:53.150
And you see that, as
speed has increased,

00:05:53.150 --> 00:05:54.990
it's just plummeted
through the floor.

00:05:54.990 --> 00:05:56.560
And the same thing
has not happened

00:05:56.560 --> 00:06:01.140
to our ability to rewrite DNA--
the ability to make sequences.

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:05.305
So I sort of make this akin
to-- we have this giant library

00:06:05.305 --> 00:06:05.930
in front of us.

00:06:05.930 --> 00:06:07.132
And now we're able to
go through and we're

00:06:07.132 --> 00:06:08.779
able to read this
entire library.

00:06:08.779 --> 00:06:10.570
And it's not necessarily
as simple as this.

00:06:10.570 --> 00:06:13.110
But let's say we have
something in there, right?

00:06:13.110 --> 00:06:14.920
We would be able to
find that sequence-- be

00:06:14.920 --> 00:06:16.250
able to find that word.

00:06:16.250 --> 00:06:18.330
And what genome editing
is really all about

00:06:18.330 --> 00:06:21.441
is adding the Find/Replace of
Word on top of that library.

00:06:21.441 --> 00:06:21.940
OK?

00:06:21.940 --> 00:06:23.250
We want to be able
to say, there's

00:06:23.250 --> 00:06:24.600
something wrong in this library.

00:06:24.600 --> 00:06:25.304
Right?

00:06:25.304 --> 00:06:27.720
Maybe someone has cancer, and
we want them to be a dancer.

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:30.290
And let's replace that C. OK?

00:06:30.290 --> 00:06:33.307
So, what is gene editing?

00:06:33.307 --> 00:06:34.890
Gene editing comes
down to our ability

00:06:34.890 --> 00:06:37.770
to use tools and change
genetic sequence.

00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:39.740
And the way that we've
done that in the past

00:06:39.740 --> 00:06:41.200
are two technologies.

00:06:41.200 --> 00:06:43.650
So in the '90s, so-called
zinc-finger nucleases

00:06:43.650 --> 00:06:44.640
were invented.

00:06:44.640 --> 00:06:46.670
These are protein-based
recognition modules.

00:06:46.670 --> 00:06:49.280
So you're using proteins
to recognize DNA.

00:06:49.280 --> 00:06:51.162
And so you have to
reprogram the protein.

00:06:51.162 --> 00:06:53.120
And it's very hard, and
it takes a lot of work,

00:06:53.120 --> 00:06:55.120
but a couple of companies
and a couple of people

00:06:55.120 --> 00:06:56.860
got quite good at it.

00:06:56.860 --> 00:07:00.460
It takes about $3,000 and 10 to
12 weeks to make one of these.

00:07:00.460 --> 00:07:02.900
So it's not super paralyzable,
but you can do it.

00:07:02.900 --> 00:07:05.110
And so this really
remains sort of something

00:07:05.110 --> 00:07:08.214
that a couple of people would
do and a couple of people

00:07:08.214 --> 00:07:10.630
would be good at, but you'd
have to collaborate with them,

00:07:10.630 --> 00:07:13.520
if you'd want to do
that kind of thing.

00:07:13.520 --> 00:07:16.610
Then in 2009 came TAL
effector nucleases.

00:07:16.610 --> 00:07:17.870
These were a bit more modular.

00:07:17.870 --> 00:07:20.520
So each protein
module recognized

00:07:20.520 --> 00:07:21.820
one set of base pairs.

00:07:21.820 --> 00:07:23.680
And so you could
stack them together.

00:07:23.680 --> 00:07:26.464
They ended up being a little
tricky to make, sometimes,

00:07:26.464 --> 00:07:27.880
but people got
quite good at them.

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:30.180
They were able to automate
that kind of synthesis.

00:07:30.180 --> 00:07:31.980
And it seemed to
work pretty well.

00:07:31.980 --> 00:07:35.232
TALENs are actually quite good.

00:07:35.232 --> 00:07:37.190
However, I sort of feel
bad for the people that

00:07:37.190 --> 00:07:38.820
invested a lot of
time in TALENs,

00:07:38.820 --> 00:07:41.020
because what came along
only three years later

00:07:41.020 --> 00:07:43.270
was this thing
called CRISPR/Cas9.

00:07:43.270 --> 00:07:45.859
So there's still reasons to
use TALENs and still reasons

00:07:45.859 --> 00:07:48.400
to using fingers, and there are
all these kinds of, you know,

00:07:48.400 --> 00:07:51.710
compare/contrast articles
that people read and write.

00:07:51.710 --> 00:07:54.800
And I think what's really
important is we have a toolbox

00:07:54.800 --> 00:07:55.300
now.

00:07:55.300 --> 00:07:55.540
Right?

00:07:55.540 --> 00:07:58.120
And we used to have one tool,
and then we had two tools,

00:07:58.120 --> 00:08:00.510
and now we have three tools,
and they're all very good,

00:08:00.510 --> 00:08:01.930
and they all have
their purposes.

00:08:01.930 --> 00:08:03.960
And so I think this
is-- as you'll see,

00:08:03.960 --> 00:08:06.840
it's the start of an upward
trend in genome editing,

00:08:06.840 --> 00:08:07.720
in general.

00:08:07.720 --> 00:08:10.270
So what CRISPR/Cas9
is it's a protein,

00:08:10.270 --> 00:08:12.070
it holds onto a
piece of RNA, and it

00:08:12.070 --> 00:08:15.080
uses that RNA to make a cut.

00:08:15.080 --> 00:08:18.080
And since it's
using DNA-- that is,

00:08:18.080 --> 00:08:20.580
DNA that gets made into an
RNA-- to do the recognition,

00:08:20.580 --> 00:08:22.740
it's very cheap,
and it's very fast,

00:08:22.740 --> 00:08:24.810
and it's very easy
to reprogram this.

00:08:24.810 --> 00:08:27.370
To give you an idea of
how fast, cheap, and easy,

00:08:27.370 --> 00:08:30.240
at this point we typically
have undergraduates

00:08:30.240 --> 00:08:32.386
who are learning how
to do PCR prepare

00:08:32.386 --> 00:08:34.010
some of this
genome-targeting reagents.

00:08:34.010 --> 00:08:36.020
So people that have never
touched a pipette before,

00:08:36.020 --> 00:08:37.490
they learn how to
do it by making

00:08:37.490 --> 00:08:39.500
genome-targeting
reagents for other people

00:08:39.500 --> 00:08:43.120
in the lab to do
genome-targeting experiments.

00:08:43.120 --> 00:08:45.430
So I think it's really
important to stress

00:08:45.430 --> 00:08:48.050
where CRISPR/Cas9 comes
from, because it's

00:08:48.050 --> 00:08:49.470
sort of this crazy tool.

00:08:49.470 --> 00:08:52.390
And you might want to ask, well,
how did such a thing exist?

00:08:52.390 --> 00:08:56.259
At its heart, Cas9 stems from
bacterial immune systems.

00:08:56.259 --> 00:08:57.550
And these are called "CRISPRs."

00:08:57.550 --> 00:09:00.390
CRISPR stands for Cluster
of Regularly Interspaced

00:09:00.390 --> 00:09:01.410
Palindromic Repeats.

00:09:01.410 --> 00:09:04.440
And that's because you have
these things called CRISPR loci

00:09:04.440 --> 00:09:06.550
that sit in bacteria.

00:09:06.550 --> 00:09:07.820
Where do they come from?

00:09:07.820 --> 00:09:10.140
When a virus infects
a bacteria-- that

00:09:10.140 --> 00:09:12.110
is, when a bacteria
gets the flu--

00:09:12.110 --> 00:09:14.177
it's injecting into
DNA into the bacteria.

00:09:14.177 --> 00:09:16.260
And the bacteria needs to
do something about that,

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:18.280
because it may have some
negative consequence.

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:19.990
And so it's developed
machinery to take

00:09:19.990 --> 00:09:22.730
bits of the viral genome
and incorporate it

00:09:22.730 --> 00:09:23.790
into its own genome.

00:09:23.790 --> 00:09:25.830
And people first
discovered CRISPR arrays

00:09:25.830 --> 00:09:28.760
when they started noticing
that parts of bacterial genomes

00:09:28.760 --> 00:09:31.684
were exactly the same as
small parts of viral genomes.

00:09:31.684 --> 00:09:33.100
And it turns out
that what happens

00:09:33.100 --> 00:09:36.380
is the bacteria then
makes RNA off of this.

00:09:36.380 --> 00:09:39.900
So it incorporates
into the CRISPR array

00:09:39.900 --> 00:09:41.670
through a process
called "adaptation."

00:09:41.670 --> 00:09:44.120
It then makes RNA
off of the array.

00:09:44.120 --> 00:09:47.010
That gets separated into
these so-called "crRNAs."

00:09:47.010 --> 00:09:50.550
Remember, these crRNAs are
now RNAs that stemmed back

00:09:50.550 --> 00:09:53.330
from this original sequence.

00:09:53.330 --> 00:09:55.860
Cas proteins, of which
Cas9 is one of them,

00:09:55.860 --> 00:09:59.590
recognize those RNAs and
use them to guide back.

00:09:59.590 --> 00:10:02.120
So they complete the circle.

00:10:02.120 --> 00:10:04.570
So you start with
viral DNA, and you

00:10:04.570 --> 00:10:06.550
have to find some way
to rerecognize that.

00:10:06.550 --> 00:10:10.150
And what the Cas proteins do
is they then cut at that site.

00:10:10.150 --> 00:10:13.000
And the really fundamental
recognition, here,

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:14.750
is that this doesn't
have to be viral DNA.

00:10:14.750 --> 00:10:19.430
You can program these with any
kind of RNA to cut anything.

00:10:19.430 --> 00:10:21.720
So let's zoom in a little
bit into how this works.

00:10:21.720 --> 00:10:24.010
Cas9 is monomeric protein.

00:10:24.010 --> 00:10:26.520
It has an RNA that it binds.

00:10:26.520 --> 00:10:28.374
So there's a little
constant region.

00:10:28.374 --> 00:10:30.290
And then there's one
little bit that you vary.

00:10:30.290 --> 00:10:33.740
And this can be 20 bases
or so-- 18 to 20 bases.

00:10:33.740 --> 00:10:35.400
And we call it
the "protospacer."

00:10:35.400 --> 00:10:37.910
And all you have to do is
know that A goes with T

00:10:37.910 --> 00:10:41.180
and G goes with C. And you
can then program it to bind

00:10:41.180 --> 00:10:43.210
and then cut anywhere
in the genome.

00:10:43.210 --> 00:10:45.630
So you just take
this constant region,

00:10:45.630 --> 00:10:47.970
and you add any
protospacer that you want,

00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:50.380
and Cas9 will cut there,
so long as-- there's

00:10:50.380 --> 00:10:52.620
only one restriction--
there's a short sequence,

00:10:52.620 --> 00:10:55.440
here, called a "protospacer
adjacent motif" also

00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:57.270
in that genome.

00:10:57.270 --> 00:10:59.830
For some organisms
that make Cas9,

00:10:59.830 --> 00:11:01.560
this ends up being three bases.

00:11:01.560 --> 00:11:03.210
For others, it's a
little bit longer.

00:11:03.210 --> 00:11:04.640
They're now a couple
of different enzymes

00:11:04.640 --> 00:11:06.060
that have different
requirements.

00:11:06.060 --> 00:11:08.476
But that means, again, that
our toolbox is getting larger.

00:11:08.476 --> 00:11:11.250
We can target more and
more and more sequence.

00:11:11.250 --> 00:11:12.820
Cas9 then makes a
double-stranded cut

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:14.680
and has two active sites.

00:11:14.680 --> 00:11:17.670
And so it cuts both
of those places.

00:11:17.670 --> 00:11:19.500
So it's very easily
reprogrammed.

00:11:19.500 --> 00:11:22.285
And we can target it using
simple rules of base pairing.

00:11:22.285 --> 00:11:24.070
If the model hasn't
gone around you yet,

00:11:24.070 --> 00:11:27.240
this is what it looks like in
3D space, rather than a cartoon.

00:11:27.240 --> 00:11:30.410
There's a guide
RNA, and it's really

00:11:30.410 --> 00:11:32.500
wrapped around the molecule.

00:11:32.500 --> 00:11:35.060
There's a duplex of DNA,
coming in on either side, which

00:11:35.060 --> 00:11:36.160
gets separated.

00:11:36.160 --> 00:11:37.660
If we take off that
one bit, you can

00:11:37.660 --> 00:11:40.840
see the RNA itself is wrapped
all the way around the DNA.

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:41.340
OK?

00:11:41.340 --> 00:11:43.090
And something-- we
still don't quite

00:11:43.090 --> 00:11:46.250
know what it is--
something tells Cas9,

00:11:46.250 --> 00:11:48.840
once it's made all the
wraps, I need to cut now.

00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:49.340
And these--

00:11:49.340 --> 00:11:52.180
Again, this is a
very emerging field.

00:11:52.180 --> 00:11:54.040
We still don't know
what triggers it to cut.

00:11:54.040 --> 00:11:56.760
You can make Cas9s that go
to a place and do nothing,

00:11:56.760 --> 00:11:57.610
and they don't cut.

00:11:57.610 --> 00:12:00.650
So there's still a lot of
mysteries to be worked out.

00:12:00.650 --> 00:12:03.090
Once you've made the
cut, you get editing.

00:12:03.090 --> 00:12:03.910
Right?

00:12:03.910 --> 00:12:06.510
But Cas9-- I really want
to stress this-- Cas9

00:12:06.510 --> 00:12:08.680
is not the thing
doing the editing.

00:12:08.680 --> 00:12:12.170
In terms of zinc fingers,
TALENs, and Cas9,

00:12:12.170 --> 00:12:14.570
all Cas9 does is make
a double-stranded cut

00:12:14.570 --> 00:12:15.570
inside the genome.

00:12:15.570 --> 00:12:17.650
And it turns out that
the host genome--

00:12:17.650 --> 00:12:19.140
the thing that you
put it into-- is

00:12:19.140 --> 00:12:22.000
taking care of the repair,
which does the edit.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.010
And so, if you make
edits in human cells,

00:12:24.010 --> 00:12:26.750
if you make edits in model
species, like Drosophila,

00:12:26.750 --> 00:12:28.862
it's their cells that are
actually doing the edit.

00:12:28.862 --> 00:12:31.320
And that's because there are
a couple of different pathways

00:12:31.320 --> 00:12:33.572
to repair double-strand
breaks in cells.

00:12:33.572 --> 00:12:35.780
Cells really care about
having a double-strand break.

00:12:35.780 --> 00:12:37.330
You can imagine that, if you
get a double-strand break

00:12:37.330 --> 00:12:38.913
in your cell, that's
not a good thing.

00:12:38.913 --> 00:12:41.130
You need to somehow get
those pieces back together.

00:12:41.130 --> 00:12:43.370
And so there are all kinds
of break-repair machinery

00:12:43.370 --> 00:12:45.580
in your cells.

00:12:45.580 --> 00:12:48.350
There's one, which is
dominant, called NHEJ.

00:12:48.350 --> 00:12:50.026
This is an error-prone process.

00:12:50.026 --> 00:12:52.150
So if you make a double-strand
break, at that point

00:12:52.150 --> 00:12:54.170
you get variable-length
so-called indels,

00:12:54.170 --> 00:12:55.350
or insertions or deletions.

00:12:55.350 --> 00:12:56.725
As you might
expect, this kind of

00:12:56.725 --> 00:12:58.790
screws up the sequence
that is in there.

00:12:58.790 --> 00:13:00.990
And so this makes what
we call "knockout."

00:13:00.990 --> 00:13:04.200
Think of this as, like, a sword
that you're going to go in

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:05.340
and chop it into a gene.

00:13:05.340 --> 00:13:06.840
And you might do
this, when you want

00:13:06.840 --> 00:13:08.190
to say, what does this gene do?

00:13:08.190 --> 00:13:09.530
This is a very classic
thing in biology.

00:13:09.530 --> 00:13:11.360
You want to know what a gene
does, so you take a model

00:13:11.360 --> 00:13:12.985
system and you break
that gene and say,

00:13:12.985 --> 00:13:15.720
what happened after I broke it?

00:13:15.720 --> 00:13:17.720
One thing that has a lot
of people very excited,

00:13:17.720 --> 00:13:20.720
though, is so-called
Homology-Directed Repair,

00:13:20.720 --> 00:13:21.439
or HDR.

00:13:21.439 --> 00:13:23.730
This is where you make the
cut and you provide a donor.

00:13:23.730 --> 00:13:26.010
And this donor has
a different sequence

00:13:26.010 --> 00:13:27.650
than what was in there before.

00:13:27.650 --> 00:13:29.280
The cell then incorporates that.

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:31.840
These dashed arrows are meant
to say we actually don't

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:33.040
know what's going on here.

00:13:33.040 --> 00:13:35.380
There's some emerging
data, maybe a little bit

00:13:35.380 --> 00:13:37.330
of which I'll talk
about, suggesting

00:13:37.330 --> 00:13:41.050
that this is not what people
classically think of as HR.

00:13:41.050 --> 00:13:43.490
But what this does is
it does precise editing.

00:13:43.490 --> 00:13:45.400
So instead of
disrupting what's there,

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:48.910
you're able to very precisely
flip in certain sequences.

00:13:48.910 --> 00:13:51.620
The problem is, this happens
at much lower efficiency

00:13:51.620 --> 00:13:52.390
than knockout.

00:13:52.390 --> 00:13:53.806
And so this is
something that lets

00:13:53.806 --> 00:13:55.690
you test what does
this gene do and may

00:13:55.690 --> 00:13:57.690
be applicable in some
therapeutic cases.

00:13:57.690 --> 00:14:00.200
But, in any case where
you saw, say, this person

00:14:00.200 --> 00:14:05.120
had a disease that was caused
by certain mutation-- maybe

00:14:05.120 --> 00:14:07.185
they had a severe
combined immunodeficiency.

00:14:07.185 --> 00:14:10.890
And we'll talk about so-called
"autologous bone-marrow

00:14:10.890 --> 00:14:11.530
transplant."

00:14:11.530 --> 00:14:12.900
If you wanted to
correct that and then

00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:14.580
transplant edited
stuff back into them,

00:14:14.580 --> 00:14:15.790
you'd have to make an edit.

00:14:15.790 --> 00:14:16.424
OK?

00:14:16.424 --> 00:14:18.840
So this is useful for asking,
what does this very specific

00:14:18.840 --> 00:14:19.820
part do?

00:14:19.820 --> 00:14:21.960
What do these specific bases do?

00:14:21.960 --> 00:14:24.810
And can we cure diseases?

00:14:24.810 --> 00:14:28.360
Now it turns out that Cas9 can
be adopted to do other things.

00:14:28.360 --> 00:14:31.250
So if you take the active
sites and you mutate them,

00:14:31.250 --> 00:14:34.150
at that point Cas9 is going to
different parts of the genome,

00:14:34.150 --> 00:14:35.450
but it's not cutting them.

00:14:35.450 --> 00:14:37.920
And so people then take
different so-called "effector

00:14:37.920 --> 00:14:39.730
proteins," and they
attach them to them.

00:14:39.730 --> 00:14:41.100
Why would you want to do this?

00:14:41.100 --> 00:14:43.730
Well, your genes are making RNA.

00:14:43.730 --> 00:14:45.940
And those RNAs are
making protein.

00:14:45.940 --> 00:14:48.020
And so, if you attach
various effectors that

00:14:48.020 --> 00:14:51.440
will either turn on or
turn off transcription,

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:53.490
making of the RNA,
it turns out that you

00:14:53.490 --> 00:14:56.560
can increase or decrease the
amount of protein that is made

00:14:56.560 --> 00:14:58.500
from certain genes-- in situ.

00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:00.620
So you don't have to be
adding something extra in.

00:15:00.620 --> 00:15:03.690
You're making extra protein
from the endogenous context.

00:15:03.690 --> 00:15:06.540
And this ends up actually
being like a rheostat.

00:15:06.540 --> 00:15:07.850
You can tune this.

00:15:07.850 --> 00:15:10.690
So it's a matter of not
just coming in with a sword

00:15:10.690 --> 00:15:11.950
or coming in with a scalpel.

00:15:11.950 --> 00:15:14.116
You're going to say, I'm
going to turn this gene up,

00:15:14.116 --> 00:15:16.880
or I'm going to turn this
gene down, and figure out what

00:15:16.880 --> 00:15:19.959
dosage does, in this system.

00:15:19.959 --> 00:15:21.500
But I think probably
what most people

00:15:21.500 --> 00:15:23.730
have heard about,
for gene editing,

00:15:23.730 --> 00:15:26.575
is its ability to maybe
be therapeutic someday.

00:15:26.575 --> 00:15:28.970
And so I wanted to
talk about what might

00:15:28.970 --> 00:15:30.430
be possible in the near term.

00:15:30.430 --> 00:15:33.424
So, at this point, we're not
talking about germ-line editing

00:15:33.424 --> 00:15:34.340
or anything like that.

00:15:34.340 --> 00:15:36.310
I share some of
the thoughts about,

00:15:36.310 --> 00:15:40.180
is that really going to do
something in the short term?

00:15:40.180 --> 00:15:42.760
In the short term, what
we're talking about

00:15:42.760 --> 00:15:46.450
is so-called
"hematopoietic" diseases.

00:15:46.450 --> 00:15:48.660
These are diseases
of the blood system.

00:15:48.660 --> 00:15:51.750
And so this is cases
where, right now,

00:15:51.750 --> 00:15:54.070
if someone has a
bone-marrow disease,

00:15:54.070 --> 00:15:55.660
you might take a
healthy donor and do

00:15:55.660 --> 00:15:57.750
a so-called
"allogeneic" transplant

00:15:57.750 --> 00:15:59.140
into the person
with the disease.

00:15:59.140 --> 00:16:01.069
You'd have to get rid
of the bone marrow.

00:16:01.069 --> 00:16:02.610
And that would then
cure the disease.

00:16:02.610 --> 00:16:03.110
OK?

00:16:03.110 --> 00:16:05.120
So the bone marrow has
some mutation in it.

00:16:05.120 --> 00:16:07.050
Maybe it's making
sickle hemoglobin,

00:16:07.050 --> 00:16:09.060
maybe it's not
making B or T cells.

00:16:09.060 --> 00:16:11.600
And so you ablate
the bad bone marrow

00:16:11.600 --> 00:16:13.790
and put in healthy bone
marrow from the donor.

00:16:13.790 --> 00:16:15.530
This has a couple
of complications.

00:16:15.530 --> 00:16:17.330
There's graft-versus-host
disease,

00:16:17.330 --> 00:16:19.440
people have to be on
immunosuppressants,

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:21.140
and so it has problems.

00:16:21.140 --> 00:16:23.070
But it works, and
it works very well

00:16:23.070 --> 00:16:26.000
and provides a really
good proof of concept

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:29.590
for the next, which is so-called
"autologous" transplant.

00:16:29.590 --> 00:16:31.540
So when people talk
about gene editing

00:16:31.540 --> 00:16:33.767
for hematopoietic
disease, we're actually

00:16:33.767 --> 00:16:35.350
talking about something
that might not

00:16:35.350 --> 00:16:36.440
be that far in the future.

00:16:36.440 --> 00:16:37.920
Because here we don't
have to worry about,

00:16:37.920 --> 00:16:39.586
like, how are we going
to edit a tissue?

00:16:39.586 --> 00:16:41.307
Like, someone with
muscular dystrophy--

00:16:41.307 --> 00:16:43.140
how do we get it into
the bone, or how do we

00:16:43.140 --> 00:16:44.880
get into the muscle?

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:46.570
We're talking about
doing something

00:16:46.570 --> 00:16:48.990
pretty similar to what
I just told you about.

00:16:48.990 --> 00:16:52.796
Instead of taking bone marrow
from an unaffected person,

00:16:52.796 --> 00:16:55.170
we're going to take bone marrow
from the affected person,

00:16:55.170 --> 00:16:57.950
correct that gene, and then just
put it right back into there.

00:16:57.950 --> 00:16:59.610
And that would be
just as curative

00:16:59.610 --> 00:17:01.240
as taking from a
different person.

00:17:01.240 --> 00:17:02.900
But there's no
host-versus-graft.

00:17:02.900 --> 00:17:03.986
You are your own donor.

00:17:03.986 --> 00:17:05.569
There's an unlimited
number of donors,

00:17:05.569 --> 00:17:06.790
because you are your own donor.

00:17:06.790 --> 00:17:08.280
You don't have to
worry about matching.

00:17:08.280 --> 00:17:10.196
And so this is, I think,
why people are really

00:17:10.196 --> 00:17:11.650
excited about this possibility.

00:17:11.650 --> 00:17:12.150
Right?

00:17:12.150 --> 00:17:14.410
We're already doing
this, except we

00:17:14.410 --> 00:17:16.842
have the dangers of taking
bone marrow from other people.

00:17:16.842 --> 00:17:19.050
We just want to be able to
take from the same person.

00:17:19.050 --> 00:17:21.175
Now there are, of course,
a lot of safety concerns.

00:17:21.175 --> 00:17:23.359
How specific are the reagents?

00:17:23.359 --> 00:17:25.940
How are we going to achieve
the right amounts of editing?

00:17:25.940 --> 00:17:28.030
What are the right
amounts of editing?

00:17:28.030 --> 00:17:30.220
I think these are
very open questions.

00:17:30.220 --> 00:17:33.160
There's a lot of work going
on by very smart people.

00:17:33.160 --> 00:17:36.876
And well get answers to
those hopefully soon.

00:17:36.876 --> 00:17:39.000
I wanted to point out that
gene editing is not just

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:40.630
for genetic disease.

00:17:40.630 --> 00:17:42.660
For curing genetic disease.

00:17:42.660 --> 00:17:44.160
People can use it
in research cases,

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:46.670
say, to model cancer in vivo.

00:17:46.670 --> 00:17:49.010
People have shown that you
can edit primary human T

00:17:49.010 --> 00:17:51.640
cells to try to figure
out immune function.

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:54.140
And people have also sort
of turned this on its head.

00:17:54.140 --> 00:17:57.230
Instead of having
bacteria-killing viruses

00:17:57.230 --> 00:18:00.320
through CRISPR, they
actually had phage viruses

00:18:00.320 --> 00:18:02.066
killing bacteria using CRISPR.

00:18:02.066 --> 00:18:03.940
So some people have made
actually pretty good

00:18:03.940 --> 00:18:05.170
antibacterials out of this.

00:18:05.170 --> 00:18:07.980
So there's a lot of
different things you can do.

00:18:07.980 --> 00:18:10.940
I think that that brings up one
other really important point,

00:18:10.940 --> 00:18:13.150
which is it seems-- so
far, at least-- Cas9

00:18:13.150 --> 00:18:15.040
is very generally applicable.

00:18:15.040 --> 00:18:18.140
So it works in bacteria,
it works in yeast,

00:18:18.140 --> 00:18:20.320
it works in flies,
it works in worms.

00:18:20.320 --> 00:18:23.640
It works in a lot of
different model systems.

00:18:23.640 --> 00:18:27.310
Sort of presaging some of the
things that we've heard about.

00:18:27.310 --> 00:18:30.250
And maybe the end of my
talk-- relatively recently,

00:18:30.250 --> 00:18:32.190
people showed that
it works in monkeys.

00:18:32.190 --> 00:18:34.950
And that should give you
a hint of what's coming

00:18:34.950 --> 00:18:37.330
and the types of discussions
that people are having.

00:18:37.330 --> 00:18:40.980
It works in a variety of
agricultural crops-- wheat,

00:18:40.980 --> 00:18:44.190
rice, sorghum, maize--
all kinds of things.

00:18:44.190 --> 00:18:46.650
And it works in human cells.

00:18:46.650 --> 00:18:49.660
One thing that I think is really
exciting, though, in terms

00:18:49.660 --> 00:18:52.700
of working in nonhuman
systems, is that Cas9 also

00:18:52.700 --> 00:18:54.815
works in nonmodel organisms.

00:18:54.815 --> 00:18:57.440
Nonmodel organisms are so called
because maybe you have trouble

00:18:57.440 --> 00:18:58.570
growing them in the lab.

00:18:58.570 --> 00:19:00.230
But one other reason
something might

00:19:00.230 --> 00:19:03.400
be a nonmodel organism is that
it so-called, quote-unquote,

00:19:03.400 --> 00:19:04.490
"has no genetics."

00:19:04.490 --> 00:19:04.990
Right?

00:19:04.990 --> 00:19:06.770
Maybe you've
sequenced the genome,

00:19:06.770 --> 00:19:08.200
you kind of know
where genes are,

00:19:08.200 --> 00:19:09.635
you don't have any way
to do anything with them,

00:19:09.635 --> 00:19:11.160
to figure out what
those genes are.

00:19:11.160 --> 00:19:15.380
And people have now shown that,
for example, cyanobacteria,

00:19:15.380 --> 00:19:18.520
mosquitoes, butterflies,
goats, cows,

00:19:18.520 --> 00:19:21.750
chickens can all be
edited using Cas9.

00:19:21.750 --> 00:19:23.380
And I think this is
really important,

00:19:23.380 --> 00:19:25.370
because instead of
now learning something

00:19:25.370 --> 00:19:29.170
about life and about the world
by looking at these few model

00:19:29.170 --> 00:19:31.350
organisms-- right?
--flies, worms--

00:19:31.350 --> 00:19:32.780
we can look at almost anything.

00:19:32.780 --> 00:19:35.689
There's someone in my department
who works on this really--

00:19:35.689 --> 00:19:36.980
I can't even remember the name.

00:19:36.980 --> 00:19:38.480
It's this crazy
little crustacean.

00:19:38.480 --> 00:19:40.021
No one else in the
world works on it.

00:19:40.021 --> 00:19:42.790
But it turns out that it does
limb regeneration like crazy.

00:19:42.790 --> 00:19:43.290
Right?

00:19:43.290 --> 00:19:45.270
You can cut off any of its
limbs, and it'll grow back.

00:19:45.270 --> 00:19:47.144
And no one knows why,
because they don't have

00:19:47.144 --> 00:19:49.150
any kind of genetics for it.

00:19:49.150 --> 00:19:51.267
And so he put Cas9 into
it, and he ejected it.

00:19:51.267 --> 00:19:53.225
He targeted this thing
called a "Hox gene" that

00:19:53.225 --> 00:19:54.830
does body patterning,
and he found out

00:19:54.830 --> 00:19:58.042
that he can make
antennae instead of limbs

00:19:58.042 --> 00:19:59.250
for those particular regions.

00:19:59.250 --> 00:20:00.916
And those antennae
will regenerate, too.

00:20:00.916 --> 00:20:03.100
So there's something that's
controlling regeneration

00:20:03.100 --> 00:20:04.049
of this body part.

00:20:04.049 --> 00:20:05.590
It opens up huge
amounts of questions

00:20:05.590 --> 00:20:07.740
that you can ask on a
very fundamental level.

00:20:07.740 --> 00:20:10.196
So I think it's really
transformative, not just

00:20:10.196 --> 00:20:12.320
in the way that I think
people have been stressing,

00:20:12.320 --> 00:20:14.900
in terms of health
and cell biology,

00:20:14.900 --> 00:20:17.140
but also just our basic,
fundamental understanding

00:20:17.140 --> 00:20:19.930
of what makes life life--
what makes an organism

00:20:19.930 --> 00:20:23.000
an organism, how do
organisms develop.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:26.100
And I think that is
really the one take-home

00:20:26.100 --> 00:20:28.100
that I'd like everybody
to take from this, which

00:20:28.100 --> 00:20:29.950
is that, in the
past gene editing

00:20:29.950 --> 00:20:33.540
was about systems that were
relatively difficult to use--

00:20:33.540 --> 00:20:34.840
relatively specialized.

00:20:34.840 --> 00:20:37.087
And so a lot of different
people would have ideas,

00:20:37.087 --> 00:20:38.920
and they would have to
funnel through people

00:20:38.920 --> 00:20:40.410
that were gene editors.

00:20:40.410 --> 00:20:40.920
OK?

00:20:40.920 --> 00:20:42.420
And that produced
kind of a blockade

00:20:42.420 --> 00:20:44.690
in the types of questions
that you would ask.

00:20:44.690 --> 00:20:48.160
Whereas what Cas9 seems to be
doing-- it's very inclusive.

00:20:48.160 --> 00:20:50.559
Almost anyone can
get it to work.

00:20:50.559 --> 00:20:52.600
There have been courses,
here, on the East Coast.

00:20:52.600 --> 00:20:55.255
We've run courses at the
IGI, just teaching people

00:20:55.255 --> 00:20:56.130
how to do this stuff.

00:20:56.130 --> 00:20:57.650
We've put protocols online.

00:20:57.650 --> 00:21:00.150
There are all sorts of freely
available reagents for helping

00:21:00.150 --> 00:21:01.310
people do this stuff.

00:21:01.310 --> 00:21:03.940
And I think that's led to a
very inclusive technology,

00:21:03.940 --> 00:21:06.010
so that, when you
have a question,

00:21:06.010 --> 00:21:07.980
you can ask and answer
that question yourself.

00:21:07.980 --> 00:21:10.680
And it's hugely accelerated
the pace of research.

00:21:10.680 --> 00:21:12.380
To illustrate
that, I just wanted

00:21:12.380 --> 00:21:15.260
to show you how fast
publications on Cas9

00:21:15.260 --> 00:21:16.220
are exploding.

00:21:16.220 --> 00:21:18.250
So if you're a
biologist and you look

00:21:18.250 --> 00:21:20.410
at PubMed, which is a
database of publications,

00:21:20.410 --> 00:21:22.960
you've probably noticed
something like this.

00:21:22.960 --> 00:21:25.920
After a couple of
initial papers, I mean,

00:21:25.920 --> 00:21:27.470
this has just exploded.

00:21:27.470 --> 00:21:29.850
I actually got these
numbers in 2015.

00:21:29.850 --> 00:21:33.621
This is the number of
papers in PubMed per week.

00:21:33.621 --> 00:21:36.120
So there' ve been about 1,000
publications in the last three

00:21:36.120 --> 00:21:37.820
years.

00:21:37.820 --> 00:21:40.500
In the last week,
there were four.

00:21:40.500 --> 00:21:41.664
So it's really exploded.

00:21:41.664 --> 00:21:43.830
And it's not like these are
all coming from one lab.

00:21:43.830 --> 00:21:45.850
I mean, that would be an
extremely prolific lab.

00:21:45.850 --> 00:21:48.400
The reason you see so many
publications is it's a tool.

00:21:48.400 --> 00:21:48.900
Right?

00:21:48.900 --> 00:21:51.060
You can ask whatever question
you're interested in.

00:21:51.060 --> 00:21:52.090
If you're a
developmental biologist,

00:21:52.090 --> 00:21:53.400
you can ask a
developmental question.

00:21:53.400 --> 00:21:55.900
If you're a cancer biologist,
you can ask a cancer question.

00:21:55.900 --> 00:21:58.210
It's, I think, very
rapidly becoming less

00:21:58.210 --> 00:22:00.910
about the tool and more
about what questions you ask.

00:22:00.910 --> 00:22:03.940
And I think that's
really very exciting.

00:22:03.940 --> 00:22:07.080
I think in terms of, when
people think about editing

00:22:07.080 --> 00:22:11.040
of organisms, therapies,
things like that, that's really

00:22:11.040 --> 00:22:14.790
also highlighted by increasing
the number of publications that

00:22:14.790 --> 00:22:16.575
just mention the term
"genome editing."

00:22:16.575 --> 00:22:18.533
So right around the time
that Cas9 came around,

00:22:18.533 --> 00:22:20.040
there were certainly
publications down here,

00:22:20.040 --> 00:22:21.940
but they're sort of
hidden by the scale.

00:22:21.940 --> 00:22:23.860
Right around the time
Cas9 came around,

00:22:23.860 --> 00:22:26.534
and maybe the TALENs, is when
the explosion in the term

00:22:26.534 --> 00:22:28.200
"genome editing" came
in the literature.

00:22:28.200 --> 00:22:31.166
So everybody's
thinking about it now.

00:22:31.166 --> 00:22:32.290
What impact does this have?

00:22:32.290 --> 00:22:34.660
Well, today we're
already very quickly

00:22:34.660 --> 00:22:36.420
able to identify gene function.

00:22:36.420 --> 00:22:39.630
We're able to make very
fast cell and animal models.

00:22:39.630 --> 00:22:41.840
And, like I talked about
with the nonmodel organisms,

00:22:41.840 --> 00:22:43.006
we have genetics everywhere.

00:22:43.006 --> 00:22:45.182
So think of this as
working better and faster.

00:22:45.182 --> 00:22:46.890
But what's going to
happen in the future?

00:22:46.890 --> 00:22:49.990
So I say "medium term" in sort
of a very vague way, because I

00:22:49.990 --> 00:22:53.430
think this is very
soon medium term.

00:22:53.430 --> 00:22:56.270
We're going to have
actual therapies

00:22:56.270 --> 00:22:59.720
for the hematopoietic system--
the bone-marrow-transplant case

00:22:59.720 --> 00:23:00.970
that I saw.

00:23:00.970 --> 00:23:02.720
The people pushing
this in the clinic

00:23:02.720 --> 00:23:05.570
are a company called
Sangamo, in the Bay Area.

00:23:05.570 --> 00:23:08.320
I want to introduce
you to Tim Brown.

00:23:08.320 --> 00:23:10.090
He is the so-called
"Berlin patient."

00:23:10.090 --> 00:23:14.340
So he had HIV, and he got
a bone-marrow transplant

00:23:14.340 --> 00:23:15.230
for leukemia.

00:23:15.230 --> 00:23:17.680
And he was lucky enough to
get a transplant from someone

00:23:17.680 --> 00:23:19.650
who had a CCR5 mutation.

00:23:19.650 --> 00:23:21.700
And it turns out,
totally coincidentally,

00:23:21.700 --> 00:23:25.360
if you have a CCR5 mutation
it makes you immune to HIV,

00:23:25.360 --> 00:23:28.230
because the HIV virus
can no longer grab on

00:23:28.230 --> 00:23:29.460
to the immune cells.

00:23:29.460 --> 00:23:29.970
OK?

00:23:29.970 --> 00:23:31.386
And so what Sangamo
has been doing

00:23:31.386 --> 00:23:33.840
is taking Tim Brown's
mutation and taking

00:23:33.840 --> 00:23:37.060
people who have HIV--
take their own bone marrow

00:23:37.060 --> 00:23:38.630
and put that mutation into it.

00:23:38.630 --> 00:23:41.270
And so this man, right
here, has been cured of HIV

00:23:41.270 --> 00:23:44.230
by getting that mutation
with a zinc finger.

00:23:44.230 --> 00:23:45.710
I want to stress
it's zinc fingers.

00:23:45.710 --> 00:23:46.210
OK?

00:23:46.210 --> 00:23:49.150
So we're not seeing Cas9
in the clinic, right now.

00:23:49.150 --> 00:23:50.460
It's a matter of time.

00:23:50.460 --> 00:23:52.670
But we are doing this, and
I'm almost certain this

00:23:52.670 --> 00:23:53.540
is going to happen.

00:23:53.540 --> 00:23:56.410
It's letting us also build
better disease models.

00:23:56.410 --> 00:23:58.990
And synthetic biology
in general has really

00:23:58.990 --> 00:24:02.230
sat up and taken notice
of this sort of thing.

00:24:02.230 --> 00:24:04.540
In the long term,
I almost hesitate

00:24:04.540 --> 00:24:06.170
to guess what's going to happen.

00:24:06.170 --> 00:24:08.628
I mean, this is where we start
to get into science fiction.

00:24:08.628 --> 00:24:10.839
And anything I say is
going to be proven wrong.

00:24:10.839 --> 00:24:12.380
Certainly people
are already thinking

00:24:12.380 --> 00:24:14.760
about in-vivo therapies,
where maybe someone has

00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:17.240
muscular dystrophy-- which
is a disease of the muscle--

00:24:17.240 --> 00:24:18.903
and you might want to correct
that-- something that's not

00:24:18.903 --> 00:24:20.090
in the hematopoietic system.

00:24:20.090 --> 00:24:22.329
There are a lot
of problems there.

00:24:22.329 --> 00:24:23.870
People have talked
to me about things

00:24:23.870 --> 00:24:26.150
like designer organizations--
stuff like that.

00:24:26.150 --> 00:24:29.160
We heard about
personalized medicine.

00:24:29.160 --> 00:24:33.090
So one thing and I
think fast gene editing

00:24:33.090 --> 00:24:34.780
enables is personalized cures.

00:24:34.780 --> 00:24:37.384
So, just by way of
background, before I

00:24:37.384 --> 00:24:39.300
was recruited to Berkeley,
I was at Genentech.

00:24:39.300 --> 00:24:41.797
And when pharma companies are
talking about personalized

00:24:41.797 --> 00:24:44.130
medicine, they're usually
thinking on a different scale.

00:24:44.130 --> 00:24:46.004
They're thinking about--
you sequence people,

00:24:46.004 --> 00:24:47.357
and you put them in bins.

00:24:47.357 --> 00:24:49.690
Now, those bins are not,
quote-unquote, "personalized"--

00:24:49.690 --> 00:24:50.690
one or two.

00:24:50.690 --> 00:24:53.200
Those are 100,000
people, 500,000 people,

00:24:53.200 --> 00:24:53.990
a million people.

00:24:53.990 --> 00:24:54.490
OK?

00:24:54.490 --> 00:24:55.440
It's very powerful.

00:24:55.440 --> 00:24:57.790
You're making sure people
get the right medicine.

00:24:57.790 --> 00:24:59.664
But if someone has
a unique mutation,

00:24:59.664 --> 00:25:01.830
it's very difficult to think
about how to cure that.

00:25:01.830 --> 00:25:04.400
And I think when we have very
fast, cheap, and easy gene

00:25:04.400 --> 00:25:06.700
editing, that's a
technical possibility.

00:25:06.700 --> 00:25:08.997
There's still a lot
of regulatory hurdles.

00:25:08.997 --> 00:25:10.830
How do you do a clinical
trial for something

00:25:10.830 --> 00:25:12.080
when there's only one patient?

00:25:12.080 --> 00:25:14.170
What does an N-of-1
trial even look like?

00:25:14.170 --> 00:25:15.950
And these are
outstanding questions

00:25:15.950 --> 00:25:18.810
that I think that regulatory
bodies, as well as patients,

00:25:18.810 --> 00:25:21.990
need to really weigh in on.

00:25:21.990 --> 00:25:23.500
I only have two minutes left.

00:25:23.500 --> 00:25:26.800
Since this is a
science symposium,

00:25:26.800 --> 00:25:29.330
I was going to put in
leading-edge data-- stuff that

00:25:29.330 --> 00:25:30.340
is coming out of my lab.

00:25:30.340 --> 00:25:32.510
This is in review right now.

00:25:32.510 --> 00:25:34.660
All I wanted to say, since
I only have two minutes,

00:25:34.660 --> 00:25:37.310
is that we've figured out
a way to do the editing

00:25:37.310 --> 00:25:39.320
part-- the replacement
of sequences--

00:25:39.320 --> 00:25:41.070
very, very quickly and easily.

00:25:41.070 --> 00:25:44.680
So we can add patient
mutations in really quickly.

00:25:44.680 --> 00:25:47.430
We can make mutants
to test mechanism.

00:25:47.430 --> 00:25:49.830
We can start tracking
genes very easily.

00:25:49.830 --> 00:25:51.800
We can even go backwards
and we can do cures.

00:25:51.800 --> 00:25:54.141
And we can do this with
basically the same frequency

00:25:54.141 --> 00:25:55.640
that you would
normally do knockout.

00:25:55.640 --> 00:25:57.140
So it seems to work
very, very well.

00:25:57.140 --> 00:26:00.810
And we think this is going
to be a really important tool

00:26:00.810 --> 00:26:02.572
for introducing cures.

00:26:02.572 --> 00:26:04.530
I'm going to skip over
the data, unfortunately,

00:26:04.530 --> 00:26:07.190
because I sort of waxed
philosophic too long.

00:26:07.190 --> 00:26:10.310
We were really asking
how is it that Cas9

00:26:10.310 --> 00:26:11.664
works when it grabs onto DNA.

00:26:11.664 --> 00:26:13.580
What's really happening
in this question mark?

00:26:13.580 --> 00:26:16.160
And also, one thing
I want to stress,

00:26:16.160 --> 00:26:18.980
for people in the audience,
is you hear a lot about Cas9.

00:26:18.980 --> 00:26:20.580
It's only three years old.

00:26:20.580 --> 00:26:21.120
Right?

00:26:21.120 --> 00:26:23.735
The most amazing, advanced
lab in the world-- I always

00:26:23.735 --> 00:26:26.110
tell this to students-- the
most amazing, advanced person

00:26:26.110 --> 00:26:27.850
in the world has only been
working on these problems

00:26:27.850 --> 00:26:28.590
for three years.

00:26:28.590 --> 00:26:30.260
This is this huge
opportunity for people

00:26:30.260 --> 00:26:33.380
to do really amazing
work in this field.

00:26:33.380 --> 00:26:34.810
We don't understand,
really, what

00:26:34.810 --> 00:26:37.150
happens in this black
box between Cas9 cutting

00:26:37.150 --> 00:26:37.702
and editing.

00:26:37.702 --> 00:26:39.410
And there's a lot of
good reason to think

00:26:39.410 --> 00:26:41.820
that what we have assumed is
not what's really happening.

00:26:41.820 --> 00:26:43.230
I'm going to skip over the data.

00:26:43.230 --> 00:26:44.680
We found some really fun stuff.

00:26:44.680 --> 00:26:48.150
It lets us make really,
really good edits,

00:26:48.150 --> 00:26:51.650
so we can have really fantastic
conversion to edited cells.

00:26:51.650 --> 00:26:54.310
It works in a variety
of loci, and it also

00:26:54.310 --> 00:26:55.520
works in disease states.

00:26:55.520 --> 00:26:57.450
This is what happens
when I try to put data

00:26:57.450 --> 00:27:03.540
into a more sort of
broad, philosophic talk.

00:27:03.540 --> 00:27:05.140
The one thing I want
to leave you with

00:27:05.140 --> 00:27:07.223
is, really, how do we
understand this new ability?

00:27:07.223 --> 00:27:08.460
Right?

00:27:08.460 --> 00:27:10.960
It wasn't so long ago that
next-gen sequencing came around

00:27:10.960 --> 00:27:13.150
and we were able to read
genomes very, very quickly.

00:27:13.150 --> 00:27:15.970
And now we're very quickly
able to edit genomes.

00:27:15.970 --> 00:27:19.615
There are genome-wide libraries
for doing Cas9 cutting.

00:27:19.615 --> 00:27:21.740
Like I said, we have
undergraduates and high-school

00:27:21.740 --> 00:27:23.698
interns coming in and
doing this sort of stuff.

00:27:23.698 --> 00:27:25.910
It's really accessible.

00:27:25.910 --> 00:27:29.070
But I do want to point
out that trust in science

00:27:29.070 --> 00:27:30.170
is a very fragile thing.

00:27:30.170 --> 00:27:32.600
And almost everybody
in the world

00:27:32.600 --> 00:27:34.890
has a preconception of
what gene editing is,

00:27:34.890 --> 00:27:37.200
because they may have read
a science fiction story

00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:38.350
or seen a movie.

00:27:38.350 --> 00:27:39.710
Maybe they saw Gattaca.

00:27:39.710 --> 00:27:41.700
They think they know
what gene editing is.

00:27:41.700 --> 00:27:44.840
And that may or may not be
what gene editing actually,

00:27:44.840 --> 00:27:46.730
is in terms of the
technology we have

00:27:46.730 --> 00:27:49.002
and the technology
maybe in the future.

00:27:49.002 --> 00:27:50.460
And I think that's
really borne out

00:27:50.460 --> 00:27:51.834
by some of the
articles that have

00:27:51.834 --> 00:27:53.580
been written pretty recently.

00:27:53.580 --> 00:27:56.720
So, for better or worse,
I spend a lot of time

00:27:56.720 --> 00:27:59.420
talking to the press,
because I work on Cas9.

00:27:59.420 --> 00:28:01.080
And invariably,
no matter how much

00:28:01.080 --> 00:28:03.330
I try to tell them it's about
disease, that, you know,

00:28:03.330 --> 00:28:05.788
it's not about designer babies,
you end up with-- you know,

00:28:05.788 --> 00:28:08.670
The Economist had a
designer baby on the cover.

00:28:08.670 --> 00:28:09.420
It just happens.

00:28:09.420 --> 00:28:09.600
Right?

00:28:09.600 --> 00:28:11.260
Because this is what
people want to think about

00:28:11.260 --> 00:28:12.426
and they want to talk about.

00:28:12.426 --> 00:28:14.810
And I think we do need
to engage this head-on,

00:28:14.810 --> 00:28:17.140
as a community of scientists.

00:28:17.140 --> 00:28:20.049
But we need to be very
honest and open about it

00:28:20.049 --> 00:28:21.965
and talk to people about
what it really means.

00:28:21.965 --> 00:28:25.670
I want to end by saying
germ-line editing is

00:28:25.670 --> 00:28:27.870
potentially a real
thing to think about.

00:28:27.870 --> 00:28:30.210
I think that it's not
real, in terms of no one

00:28:30.210 --> 00:28:31.120
has done it yet.

00:28:31.120 --> 00:28:32.352
Someone has tried.

00:28:32.352 --> 00:28:34.310
They were never going to
implant these zygotes,

00:28:34.310 --> 00:28:37.460
but they were able to show
that they could make indels

00:28:37.460 --> 00:28:39.739
in human zygotes.

00:28:39.739 --> 00:28:41.030
These were not brought to term.

00:28:41.030 --> 00:28:43.170
There were some problems
with those edits.

00:28:43.170 --> 00:28:46.110
They had a lot of
off-targets-- things like that.

00:28:46.110 --> 00:28:49.317
As the result of seeing some
of that stuff, we at the IGI

00:28:49.317 --> 00:28:50.900
called a meeting in
Napa with a couple

00:28:50.900 --> 00:28:53.830
of people that were initially
involved in the Asilomar

00:28:53.830 --> 00:28:55.630
discussions on recombinant DNA.

00:28:55.630 --> 00:28:59.530
And after that meeting we
pushed very hard for the IOM

00:28:59.530 --> 00:29:01.760
and the NAS to take that on.

00:29:01.760 --> 00:29:03.677
Actually, today's
the second, right?

00:29:03.677 --> 00:29:05.260
I think tomorrow is
when there's going

00:29:05.260 --> 00:29:07.670
to be a-- what happens
when the NAS gets involved

00:29:07.670 --> 00:29:10.190
is now there's going to be a
premeeting to plan the meeting.

00:29:10.190 --> 00:29:11.730
And so that meeting--
the premeeting

00:29:11.730 --> 00:29:13.280
to plan the meeting
is happening tomorrow.

00:29:13.280 --> 00:29:15.810
And there's going to be a large
National Academy of Sciences

00:29:15.810 --> 00:29:18.117
meeting in December
to talk about what

00:29:18.117 --> 00:29:20.700
is human germ-line editing, what
are the guidelines around it.

00:29:20.700 --> 00:29:24.250
I think that's very important,
because right now, in the US,

00:29:24.250 --> 00:29:27.710
the FDA has said, we will
not sanction any research,

00:29:27.710 --> 00:29:30.430
at all, that involves
germ-line editing.

00:29:30.430 --> 00:29:33.130
Even if it's not for
reproductive purposes.

00:29:33.130 --> 00:29:35.920
Even if, you know, the zygotes
are going to be terminated.

00:29:35.920 --> 00:29:38.590
Even if it's going to be for
a purely basic research thing

00:29:38.590 --> 00:29:41.770
and we're just going to do the
edit, find out what genes do.

00:29:41.770 --> 00:29:43.570
It is completely not allowed.

00:29:43.570 --> 00:29:44.200
-Human.

00:29:44.200 --> 00:29:44.700
-Human.

00:29:44.700 --> 00:29:45.140
Human.

00:29:45.140 --> 00:29:45.639
Sorry.

00:29:45.639 --> 00:29:47.540
Yeah.

00:29:47.540 --> 00:29:51.540
And so I don't want to say one
way or the other-- you know,

00:29:51.540 --> 00:29:52.630
is that good, is that bad.

00:29:52.630 --> 00:29:54.380
What I want to say,
though, is right now

00:29:54.380 --> 00:29:56.310
it's this complete restriction.

00:29:56.310 --> 00:29:57.880
We called for a
temporary moratorium.

00:29:57.880 --> 00:30:01.220
We did not mean
to say, you know,

00:30:01.220 --> 00:30:02.680
no one ever do it ever again.

00:30:02.680 --> 00:30:04.950
I think that's part of
the conversation-- is what

00:30:04.950 --> 00:30:07.760
those guidelines look like.

00:30:07.760 --> 00:30:09.380
I want to end up by thanking.

00:30:09.380 --> 00:30:12.640
These are the people who
really do the work in my lab.

00:30:12.640 --> 00:30:14.680
One of my lab's
favorite things is

00:30:14.680 --> 00:30:17.555
this giant scissors that we
bought, as you might imagine.

00:30:17.555 --> 00:30:18.055
[LAUGH]

00:30:18.055 --> 00:30:18.871
[LAUGHTER]

