00:32:53.760 --> 00:32:56.357
-I'm tempted to say,
gosh, follow that.

00:32:56.357 --> 00:32:58.190
First of all, thank you
very much for asking

00:32:58.190 --> 00:33:00.125
me to come and speak to you.

00:33:00.125 --> 00:33:02.200
It's not only an
honor to come here,

00:33:02.200 --> 00:33:03.980
but I would never
refuse an opportunity

00:33:03.980 --> 00:33:05.563
to come to your
lovely city of Boston.

00:33:05.563 --> 00:33:06.350
So thank you.

00:33:08.890 --> 00:33:11.730
What I'm going to talk
about is the translation

00:33:11.730 --> 00:33:14.210
of a scientific procedure
into the clinic.

00:33:14.210 --> 00:33:16.460
And what's interesting
is that it's actually

00:33:16.460 --> 00:33:18.920
almost the present in the
UK, but it's probably still

00:33:18.920 --> 00:33:21.010
somewhere in the
future in the US.

00:33:21.010 --> 00:33:24.750
And that's why half of what
I'm going to talk about today

00:33:24.750 --> 00:33:27.020
is not about the
clinical condition

00:33:27.020 --> 00:33:29.680
or the scientific
solutions we have

00:33:29.680 --> 00:33:31.267
but actually the
way that, in the UK,

00:33:31.267 --> 00:33:33.100
we've gone about the
ethics and the politics

00:33:33.100 --> 00:33:38.450
and why it's actually managed
to get us to that situation.

00:33:38.450 --> 00:33:40.640
So, first of all,
the clinical problem.

00:33:40.640 --> 00:33:43.490
And forgive me for
very complicated slide.

00:33:43.490 --> 00:33:48.140
It's actually
deliberately complicated.

00:33:48.140 --> 00:33:51.250
Mitochondria, as
we've already heard,

00:33:51.250 --> 00:33:54.030
are little organisms within
every single cell of our body

00:33:54.030 --> 00:33:56.775
that make the energy.

00:33:56.775 --> 00:33:58.400
The number of
mitochondria and the type

00:33:58.400 --> 00:34:01.300
of mitochondria in different
organisms, in different cells,

00:34:01.300 --> 00:34:02.510
change.

00:34:02.510 --> 00:34:05.240
And therefore if a mitochondria
is defective in one

00:34:05.240 --> 00:34:07.002
particular tissue
type, it's going

00:34:07.002 --> 00:34:08.460
to give a different
sort of disease

00:34:08.460 --> 00:34:12.460
than it will be if it's
in a different issue.

00:34:12.460 --> 00:34:14.580
Also, the severity
of the condition

00:34:14.580 --> 00:34:16.362
will vary considerably,
both depending

00:34:16.362 --> 00:34:17.820
on the mutation of
the mitochondria

00:34:17.820 --> 00:34:20.350
and the number of abnormal
mitochondria in each cell.

00:34:20.350 --> 00:34:23.659
So just about any cell in
the body that requires energy

00:34:23.659 --> 00:34:27.010
has the potential to be harmed
by mitochondria disease.

00:34:27.010 --> 00:34:29.000
And therefore we
get a whole variety

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:33.929
of different clinical
situations such as this.

00:34:33.929 --> 00:34:36.600
Well, as I say, 90% of the
cellular energy within a cell

00:34:36.600 --> 00:34:38.554
comes from the mitochondria.

00:34:38.554 --> 00:34:41.750
It contains its own genome.

00:34:41.750 --> 00:34:45.973
As I said earlier, it's
thought that the mitochondria

00:34:45.973 --> 00:34:47.389
originally come
from bacteria that

00:34:47.389 --> 00:34:50.670
became incorporated into
single-cell organisms, all

00:34:50.670 --> 00:34:52.080
those years ago.

00:34:52.080 --> 00:34:53.880
And by providing all
that extra energy,

00:34:53.880 --> 00:34:55.699
that allowed all
these single cells

00:34:55.699 --> 00:34:58.180
to get together and make
complex cellular structures

00:34:58.180 --> 00:34:59.880
that we have now.

00:34:59.880 --> 00:35:03.260
There is a debate about how
much the mitochondria talks

00:35:03.260 --> 00:35:04.710
to the nucleus.

00:35:04.710 --> 00:35:06.960
And I'm not even
going to begin to talk

00:35:06.960 --> 00:35:11.002
about the complex
diagram that's there.

00:35:11.002 --> 00:35:12.460
The evidence would
suggest, though,

00:35:12.460 --> 00:35:14.530
that in clinical
practice there is not

00:35:14.530 --> 00:35:18.380
any compatibility problem
between the mitochondria

00:35:18.380 --> 00:35:19.270
and the nucleus.

00:35:19.270 --> 00:35:23.270
And that's because we
reproduce across ethnic groups

00:35:23.270 --> 00:35:23.840
quite easily.

00:35:27.310 --> 00:35:30.160
We've also heard, of course,
that the mitochondria

00:35:30.160 --> 00:35:33.410
is transmitted down
the maternal line.

00:35:33.410 --> 00:35:35.410
The sperm does obviously
have some mitochondria,

00:35:35.410 --> 00:35:36.090
because it moves.

00:35:36.090 --> 00:35:37.330
It has to have some
energy from somewhere.

00:35:37.330 --> 00:35:39.204
But it's thought that
the mitochondria that's

00:35:39.204 --> 00:35:45.670
within the sperm is removed at
the time of the fertilization.

00:35:45.670 --> 00:35:47.840
The amount of DNA,
obviously, in the nucleus

00:35:47.840 --> 00:35:52.415
is huge, compared to the amount
of DNA within mitochondria.

00:35:56.510 --> 00:35:58.514
Those who work in
the fertility field--

00:35:58.514 --> 00:36:00.680
and when I give this talk
to the fertility audience,

00:36:00.680 --> 00:36:04.030
I really, really say the first
message you must go home with

00:36:04.030 --> 00:36:06.515
is that mitochondria
transfer is not

00:36:06.515 --> 00:36:08.470
a treatment for infertility.

00:36:08.470 --> 00:36:09.932
It's nothing to do with IVF.

00:36:09.932 --> 00:36:11.640
It's a potential
treatment for people who

00:36:11.640 --> 00:36:13.470
carry mitochondrial disease.

00:36:13.470 --> 00:36:16.060
But what they've done is looked
at oocytes at different levels

00:36:16.060 --> 00:36:17.810
and looked at the copy
numbers of mitochondria

00:36:17.810 --> 00:36:18.650
within the oocytes.

00:36:18.650 --> 00:36:20.340
And you see huge variations.

00:36:20.340 --> 00:36:23.220
But actually there's no evidence
that the number of mitochondria

00:36:23.220 --> 00:36:25.690
within an oocyte have any
clinical significance,

00:36:25.690 --> 00:36:28.564
in terms of the development
potential of that egg

00:36:28.564 --> 00:36:29.480
to make an individual.

00:36:33.372 --> 00:36:35.830
So, in clinical practice, we
start to get a little bit more

00:36:35.830 --> 00:36:36.650
complicated.

00:36:36.650 --> 00:36:38.870
This is an example
from a woman who

00:36:38.870 --> 00:36:41.845
carried this particular
mutation of mitochondria.

00:36:41.845 --> 00:36:43.220
But she had
different proportions

00:36:43.220 --> 00:36:45.480
of abnormal mitochondria
in each cell in her body.

00:36:45.480 --> 00:36:47.810
So there was 18%
in her quadriceps

00:36:47.810 --> 00:36:49.740
and 7% in leucocytes.

00:36:49.740 --> 00:36:52.590
But when they then
look at her oocytes,

00:36:52.590 --> 00:36:55.040
we found that the mutation
load varied from anything

00:36:55.040 --> 00:36:58.130
from 0% to 45%.

00:36:58.130 --> 00:37:00.340
So it's going to be really
difficult to predict,

00:37:00.340 --> 00:37:02.484
for the women who carry
mitochondrial disease, what

00:37:02.484 --> 00:37:04.900
their chances are that they're
going to have a baby that's

00:37:04.900 --> 00:37:07.190
going to have a problem.

00:37:07.190 --> 00:37:09.579
Here's an example.

00:37:09.579 --> 00:37:11.620
This mum, here-- I should
say "mom," shouldn't I?

00:37:11.620 --> 00:37:12.580
I'm in the wrong place.

00:37:12.580 --> 00:37:16.046
--mom had 38%
abnormal mitochondria.

00:37:16.046 --> 00:37:17.420
She was actually
physically well.

00:37:17.420 --> 00:37:19.820
She had no clinical
significant symptoms at all.

00:37:19.820 --> 00:37:22.580
She had a daughter who had no
abnormal mitochondria at all

00:37:22.580 --> 00:37:24.540
and was almost
perfectly healthy.

00:37:24.540 --> 00:37:27.880
But her son had 78%
abnormal mitochondria,

00:37:27.880 --> 00:37:29.310
and he died at the age of seven.

00:37:32.330 --> 00:37:33.900
So what's her chances?

00:37:33.900 --> 00:37:35.440
What are her
options, if she wants

00:37:35.440 --> 00:37:38.397
to try and make sure she doesn't
have a child with a problem?

00:37:38.397 --> 00:37:40.230
Well, of course, she
can have egg donations.

00:37:40.230 --> 00:37:42.300
She can take the whole egg from
some other woman, fertilized

00:37:42.300 --> 00:37:44.320
with her husband's
sperm, put back in her.

00:37:44.320 --> 00:37:46.220
And that would give her
pretty much guarantee

00:37:46.220 --> 00:37:47.840
that she's not going
to have a child

00:37:47.840 --> 00:37:49.230
with mitochondrial disease.

00:37:49.230 --> 00:37:51.592
But it won't have any of
her nuclear genome, either.

00:37:51.592 --> 00:37:53.050
And, for a lot of
these women, this

00:37:53.050 --> 00:37:56.080
is just not something that
they would want to consider.

00:37:56.080 --> 00:37:59.230
We could do prenatal diagnosis,
we can do amniocentesis,

00:37:59.230 --> 00:38:02.300
and we can determine
what carrier

00:38:02.300 --> 00:38:03.570
the child is going to have.

00:38:03.570 --> 00:38:05.153
But obviously the
only option for then

00:38:05.153 --> 00:38:06.730
is the question
about termination.

00:38:06.730 --> 00:38:08.930
Because it's so
difficult to identify

00:38:08.930 --> 00:38:12.919
what the clinical phenotype
of that child is going to be,

00:38:12.919 --> 00:38:14.960
it makes that decision
about whether to terminate

00:38:14.960 --> 00:38:17.920
the pregnancy even
more difficult.

00:38:17.920 --> 00:38:20.590
We can do PGD, and we do do PGD.

00:38:20.590 --> 00:38:24.250
So you can take a biopsy
of an egg and a cell

00:38:24.250 --> 00:38:30.330
from an embryo at about three
days after infertilization

00:38:30.330 --> 00:38:32.844
and look at the mutation.

00:38:32.844 --> 00:38:34.510
But that's not always
very easy, either.

00:38:34.510 --> 00:38:37.950
Because you don't get, as you
would do with a nuclear DNA--

00:38:37.950 --> 00:38:39.540
you don't get a yes or no.

00:38:39.540 --> 00:38:41.122
You get a percentage.

00:38:41.122 --> 00:38:43.580
So if you're lucky and you find
that, in that cell that you

00:38:43.580 --> 00:38:46.300
take out from the embryo,
there's no mutations at all,

00:38:46.300 --> 00:38:49.166
you can probably say that
child's going to be OK.

00:38:49.166 --> 00:38:53.280
At less than 30%, there's a
lifetime risk, but it's low.

00:38:53.280 --> 00:38:55.080
Once you get higher
levels of that,

00:38:55.080 --> 00:38:58.790
you start to get an increasing
chances that that child's going

00:38:58.790 --> 00:39:01.790
to be affected.

00:39:01.790 --> 00:39:04.750
The problem we have with
PGD is that, once you

00:39:04.750 --> 00:39:08.740
start sticking a needle into
an embryo and taken cells out,

00:39:08.740 --> 00:39:10.850
you start to
compromise the embryo.

00:39:10.850 --> 00:39:15.147
Its ability to go on and
then develop and implant

00:39:15.147 --> 00:39:16.230
is going to be disruptive.

00:39:16.230 --> 00:39:20.530
So you're then not only going
to look at mutation load you've

00:39:20.530 --> 00:39:22.120
got in that embryo,
you've got to look

00:39:22.120 --> 00:39:23.370
at the quality of that embryo.

00:39:23.370 --> 00:39:25.715
Do you put back a
blastocyst, for instance,

00:39:25.715 --> 00:39:28.210
that's a really
perfectly good blastocyst

00:39:28.210 --> 00:39:31.160
but maybe have a 20% chance
of carrying a disease,

00:39:31.160 --> 00:39:35.090
or one that's not so good but
might only have a 5% but looks

00:39:35.090 --> 00:39:38.030
like it's actually going to
be more likely to implant?

00:39:38.030 --> 00:39:43.000
Complicated decisions
that need to be made.

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:46.890
But for some people,
there are better options.

00:39:46.890 --> 00:39:52.080
And that would be to try and
do mitochondrial transfer.

00:39:52.080 --> 00:39:54.220
This is not three years
old-- three months old

00:39:54.220 --> 00:39:55.990
or three years old.

00:39:55.990 --> 00:39:58.630
This is more like 15 years old.

00:39:58.630 --> 00:40:02.790
The Newcastle team, led at
that time by Doug Turnbull,

00:40:02.790 --> 00:40:06.000
spoke to the chief medical
officer in the UK at the time

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:09.070
that they were looking
at the regulations,

00:40:09.070 --> 00:40:11.891
the potential legislation
around themselves.

00:40:11.891 --> 00:40:13.390
And the document
he put forward then

00:40:13.390 --> 00:40:15.300
includes a chapter
on the potential

00:40:15.300 --> 00:40:18.150
that we saw at that time that
doing mitochondrial transfer

00:40:18.150 --> 00:40:20.169
was something that
we would start

00:40:20.169 --> 00:40:22.710
doing-- that we thought we might
be able to do in the future.

00:40:22.710 --> 00:40:24.376
And I think this was
the important thing

00:40:24.376 --> 00:40:26.670
about anticipating in advance
what was going to happen,

00:40:26.670 --> 00:40:29.290
to give ourselves time
to get the legislation

00:40:29.290 --> 00:40:30.546
through in parallel.

00:40:33.494 --> 00:40:34.910
The techniques
we're talking about

00:40:34.910 --> 00:40:37.470
was this, which is the diagram
that Janet was speaking

00:40:37.470 --> 00:40:38.850
to you about at the beginning.

00:40:38.850 --> 00:40:41.955
Basically, you take an
egg that's a donor egg.

00:40:41.955 --> 00:40:43.552
You fertilize it.

00:40:43.552 --> 00:40:45.760
And then you take out the
male and female pronucleus.

00:40:45.760 --> 00:40:49.330
So you end up with an egg
that's got no nucleus in,

00:40:49.330 --> 00:40:51.630
but it's got normal
mitochondria.

00:40:51.630 --> 00:40:53.296
You basically do the
same from the egg

00:40:53.296 --> 00:40:55.110
from the affected
woman, but then you

00:40:55.110 --> 00:40:59.260
take out the nuclear genome from
the defected woman, put it back

00:40:59.260 --> 00:41:01.690
into the donor egg, and
the resulting embryo

00:41:01.690 --> 00:41:05.040
will be a healthy child, as
far as the mitochondria is

00:41:05.040 --> 00:41:05.830
concerned.

00:41:05.830 --> 00:41:09.510
But it will be genetically
related to mum and dad.

00:41:09.510 --> 00:41:11.056
Sounds too easy, doesn't it?

00:41:11.056 --> 00:41:12.680
-[LAUGH]

00:41:12.680 --> 00:41:14.260
-Of course, in order
to do that, you

00:41:14.260 --> 00:41:16.530
have the potential that
you're going to create embryos

00:41:16.530 --> 00:41:18.447
and then you're going
to discard them.

00:41:18.447 --> 00:41:20.780
So someone said, well, why
don't we do spindle transfers

00:41:20.780 --> 00:41:21.529
as an alternative?

00:41:21.529 --> 00:41:24.750
That means taking the
genetic material from the egg

00:41:24.750 --> 00:41:27.110
before it is fertilized.

00:41:27.110 --> 00:41:31.150
Then you only need to create
an embryo with-- basically,

00:41:31.150 --> 00:41:33.670
the final embryo that
you're going to put back.

00:41:33.670 --> 00:41:36.940
The problem is that, when
you're looking at the spindle,

00:41:36.940 --> 00:41:39.090
I don't know if any of
you can see the spindle

00:41:39.090 --> 00:41:40.572
in that top, unfertilized egg.

00:41:40.572 --> 00:41:42.530
You can see it quite easy
in the fertilized egg

00:41:42.530 --> 00:41:44.410
because the male and
female chromosomes

00:41:44.410 --> 00:41:45.910
are in that little
package karyotype

00:41:45.910 --> 00:41:47.920
that you can see very clearly.

00:41:47.920 --> 00:41:50.756
You can use special polarized
light to actually see it.

00:41:50.756 --> 00:41:52.130
And you actually
see the spindle.

00:41:52.130 --> 00:41:56.764
The spindle's the line
that holds the chromosomes.

00:41:56.764 --> 00:41:58.180
But the problem
is you're not only

00:41:58.180 --> 00:41:59.417
taking out the chromosomes.

00:41:59.417 --> 00:42:01.250
You've got to take out
all the proteins that

00:42:01.250 --> 00:42:03.700
go with the spindle, to make
the spindle work properly.

00:42:03.700 --> 00:42:05.160
And then, if you're not
careful, you're going to take,

00:42:05.160 --> 00:42:07.730
potentially, some abnormal
mitochondria, to as well.

00:42:07.730 --> 00:42:10.604
So you've got to be really
careful what you do.

00:42:10.604 --> 00:42:13.020
Meiosis II, which is the state
at which you're doing this,

00:42:13.020 --> 00:42:16.130
is a really very
highly dynamic state.

00:42:16.130 --> 00:42:17.850
And it's very sensitive
to disruption.

00:42:17.850 --> 00:42:19.683
So we've really got to
be careful about what

00:42:19.683 --> 00:42:22.340
we're doing at this time.

00:42:22.340 --> 00:42:25.450
However, the
spindle-transfer technique

00:42:25.450 --> 00:42:29.010
has been shown to be successful.

00:42:29.010 --> 00:42:33.880
These are the two monkeys that
came from the Oregon group.

00:42:33.880 --> 00:42:35.970
Obviously these monkeys
are perfectly healthy,

00:42:35.970 --> 00:42:38.110
but they did actually
publish in the paper

00:42:38.110 --> 00:42:40.360
that there was quite a
high degree of abnormality

00:42:40.360 --> 00:42:42.530
in the batch of embryos
that they actually created.

00:42:42.530 --> 00:42:44.090
Although subsequent
to that I think

00:42:44.090 --> 00:42:46.090
they have improved
the technique,

00:42:46.090 --> 00:42:48.180
and they are getting
better success rates.

00:42:48.180 --> 00:42:53.220
So there are two
potential options, there--

00:42:53.220 --> 00:42:55.010
this one perhaps
compromised by the fact

00:42:55.010 --> 00:42:56.801
that they tried to take
a patent out on it.

00:42:56.801 --> 00:43:00.030
And that's a different
issue altogether.

00:43:00.030 --> 00:43:04.090
So what are the issues
that we've had to address?

00:43:04.090 --> 00:43:07.866
And this is where they've
gone down in parallel.

00:43:07.866 --> 00:43:10.490
The scientific work-- basically,
does it work, is it efficient,

00:43:10.490 --> 00:43:11.050
is it safe?

00:43:11.050 --> 00:43:12.660
That's been led by
Mary Herbert, who's

00:43:12.660 --> 00:43:14.660
a senior scientist
on laboratory,

00:43:14.660 --> 00:43:17.050
and Louise Hyslop, who's our
clinical embryologist, who

00:43:17.050 --> 00:43:19.760
really has the green
fingers to make it work.

00:43:19.760 --> 00:43:21.890
And my role has been
more going along

00:43:21.890 --> 00:43:23.991
the line of looking at
the regulatory and ethical

00:43:23.991 --> 00:43:24.490
[INAUDIBLE].

00:43:24.490 --> 00:43:26.676
How could we find to
get it to the point

00:43:26.676 --> 00:43:28.300
that it would be
legal to do in the UK?

00:43:28.300 --> 00:43:30.860
Because at this time, when
we started, it was not legal.

00:43:30.860 --> 00:43:33.160
And how would we take the
population along with us?

00:43:33.160 --> 00:43:36.091
How would we make them see
that it was actually perhaps

00:43:36.091 --> 00:43:37.590
an ethically
acceptable thing to do?

00:43:40.110 --> 00:43:43.890
So, on the science
side-- and, as I say,

00:43:43.890 --> 00:43:45.740
this is 15 years' work.

00:43:45.740 --> 00:43:51.365
First of all, Doug Turnbull and
his team did work with mice.

00:43:54.410 --> 00:43:56.950
They did the pronuclear
transfer techniques,

00:43:56.950 --> 00:43:58.640
and they got live
pups, and they showed

00:43:58.640 --> 00:44:01.030
that the mitochondria
carryover was sufficiently

00:44:01.030 --> 00:44:03.380
low to be acceptable.

00:44:03.380 --> 00:44:05.675
We then got permission from
the Human Fertilisation

00:44:05.675 --> 00:44:09.360
and Embryology Authority,
who are regulators in the UK,

00:44:09.360 --> 00:44:13.300
to do work on abnormally
fertilized human eggs.

00:44:13.300 --> 00:44:16.551
When you do IVF, you will
often end up with eggs that are

00:44:16.551 --> 00:44:19.050
fertilized but there's only one
[? pronucleus ?] [INAUDIBLE]

00:44:19.050 --> 00:44:20.675
[? with ?] the three
or more pronuclei.

00:44:20.675 --> 00:44:23.011
And in order to show that
these techniques would work,

00:44:23.011 --> 00:44:25.260
we would switch over them
over So we ended up with two

00:44:25.260 --> 00:44:27.340
and then developed them.

00:44:27.340 --> 00:44:30.430
That was the work that
was published in Nature

00:44:30.430 --> 00:44:31.806
five years ago.

00:44:31.806 --> 00:44:33.180
And, on the back
of that, we then

00:44:33.180 --> 00:44:36.890
got permission from the
HFEA to do the techniques

00:44:36.890 --> 00:44:38.200
in normal eggs.

00:44:38.200 --> 00:44:41.120
So these are eggs
donated by healthy women

00:44:41.120 --> 00:44:43.840
in order to do the procedure.

00:44:43.840 --> 00:44:47.470
We had to work out what
tests we would need to do,

00:44:47.470 --> 00:44:50.030
because not only can we
actually do the technique,

00:44:50.030 --> 00:44:53.280
but we've got to show that
it's going to be safe.

00:44:53.280 --> 00:44:55.390
So we need to look things
like do the technique

00:44:55.390 --> 00:44:58.056
and then look at the karyotype--
look at the epigenetics.

00:44:58.056 --> 00:44:59.430
We had a problem
in saying, well,

00:44:59.430 --> 00:45:00.360
in order for it
to be safe, you've

00:45:00.360 --> 00:45:01.470
got to compare it
with something.

00:45:01.470 --> 00:45:02.636
What do you compare it with?

00:45:02.636 --> 00:45:05.030
Because there isn't
a normal-type embryo

00:45:05.030 --> 00:45:07.699
that's an in-vivo embryo that
you could compare it with.

00:45:07.699 --> 00:45:09.240
And the best we
thought we could find

00:45:09.240 --> 00:45:10.890
would be the ICSI
embryos that are

00:45:10.890 --> 00:45:12.340
created, because
these are embryos

00:45:12.340 --> 00:45:13.664
what are already manipulated.

00:45:13.664 --> 00:45:15.455
They've already had
needles stuck into them

00:45:15.455 --> 00:45:17.340
as part of the IVF process.

00:45:17.340 --> 00:45:19.640
So we felt if we could
end up with embryos which,

00:45:19.640 --> 00:45:22.430
by everything that we measure,
were going be the same as ICSI,

00:45:22.430 --> 00:45:24.680
then we were probably as
good as we were going to get.

00:45:26.799 --> 00:45:28.590
Just very briefly, this
is some of the work

00:45:28.590 --> 00:45:30.470
that came from the Nature.

00:45:30.470 --> 00:45:32.050
And you see, in
figure B, you can

00:45:32.050 --> 00:45:33.760
see a one-pronuclear embryo.

00:45:33.760 --> 00:45:35.910
In C, you can see three.

00:45:35.910 --> 00:45:37.895
Basically, we take
them out, so we end up,

00:45:37.895 --> 00:45:40.680
with D, with no
nuclear material.

00:45:40.680 --> 00:45:43.490
And then we take
two, put them back,

00:45:43.490 --> 00:45:46.430
activate the cell to make
it grow, and then go on.

00:45:46.430 --> 00:45:48.760
And we get blastocysts.

00:45:48.760 --> 00:45:52.140
Unmanipulate controls were 17%.

00:45:52.140 --> 00:45:54.240
And the pronuclear-transfer
ones were 8%.

00:45:54.240 --> 00:45:56.700
Those are low, compared
to any IVF program.

00:45:56.700 --> 00:45:59.120
But don't forget these are
abnormally fertilized embryos

00:45:59.120 --> 00:46:00.590
in the first place.

00:46:00.590 --> 00:46:02.840
What we showed, basically,
are proof of principle

00:46:02.840 --> 00:46:04.381
that you could
actually do it and you

00:46:04.381 --> 00:46:08.490
could get onward development
of embryos from that.

00:46:08.490 --> 00:46:12.340
And then, of course, you want
to look at the mean carryover

00:46:12.340 --> 00:46:13.640
of the mitochondria.

00:46:13.640 --> 00:46:15.110
And the mean was less than 2%.

00:46:15.110 --> 00:46:17.590
So we felt we were getting,
in this particular study,

00:46:17.590 --> 00:46:20.805
down to levels that would
be clinically acceptable.

00:46:20.805 --> 00:46:23.180
Just as a slight sideline,
before I forget to mention it,

00:46:23.180 --> 00:46:26.300
less than 2% is the point
at which you would not

00:46:26.300 --> 00:46:30.530
expect any abnormal mitochondria
to be passed onto the germ

00:46:30.530 --> 00:46:32.949
line of any children
that will be conceived

00:46:32.949 --> 00:46:33.990
as a result of treatment.

00:46:33.990 --> 00:46:37.364
So you're not any potentially
helping this child,

00:46:37.364 --> 00:46:39.030
but you're potentially
helping, if she's

00:46:39.030 --> 00:46:40.620
a female, her children, as well.

00:46:43.159 --> 00:46:44.450
So where are we, at the moment?

00:46:44.450 --> 00:46:48.470
Well, we're getting eggs
donated from healthy volunteers.

00:46:48.470 --> 00:46:51.467
We're looking to
develop the techniques.

00:46:51.467 --> 00:46:53.050
We're looking to
evaluate the embryos,

00:46:53.050 --> 00:46:55.160
we're looking at the
mitochondrial carryover,

00:46:55.160 --> 00:46:56.910
and we're looking at
the efficiency of it.

00:46:56.910 --> 00:46:59.860
We're also working with
the scientific advisors

00:46:59.860 --> 00:47:01.690
of the HFEA, because
they're the ones we're

00:47:01.690 --> 00:47:03.231
going to have to
convince when we put

00:47:03.231 --> 00:47:05.029
an application in
to the HFEA to say,

00:47:05.029 --> 00:47:06.320
now can we do it for treatment?

00:47:06.320 --> 00:47:07.670
So we needed to
be absolutely sure

00:47:07.670 --> 00:47:09.544
that all the experiments
that they were going

00:47:09.544 --> 00:47:12.660
to ask us to do we would have
information about, so we were

00:47:12.660 --> 00:47:14.825
not running behind
ourselves, at the same time,

00:47:14.825 --> 00:47:16.200
thinking there's
going to someone

00:47:16.200 --> 00:47:18.616
that's going to trip us over,
at some point in the future.

00:47:21.720 --> 00:47:24.660
So let's move on to
regulation and ethical issues.

00:47:29.200 --> 00:47:31.700
These are all the bodies that,
in the UK, have looked at it.

00:47:31.700 --> 00:47:33.550
And I'll go through some
of these in more detail.

00:47:33.550 --> 00:47:35.530
I've put them into two big
groups, there-- one egg

00:47:35.530 --> 00:47:37.363
donation and one to
mitochondrial donation--

00:47:37.363 --> 00:47:40.720
because those who were
opposed to what we did

00:47:40.720 --> 00:47:43.950
realized very early on that
if we didn't have egg donors

00:47:43.950 --> 00:47:45.700
we couldn't do the work.

00:47:45.700 --> 00:47:48.700
So we were challenged very
heavily by people who said,

00:47:48.700 --> 00:47:50.840
it's not ethical for
you to ask young women

00:47:50.840 --> 00:47:53.320
to donate their eggs.

00:47:53.320 --> 00:47:55.930
This is different from
any other medical research

00:47:55.930 --> 00:47:57.695
where we have
healthy volunteers.

00:47:57.695 --> 00:47:59.800
And a lot of very
sensible people

00:47:59.800 --> 00:48:03.025
thought that they knew better
than the women themselves

00:48:03.025 --> 00:48:04.400
who were coming
to us and saying,

00:48:04.400 --> 00:48:07.990
yes, we will help donate, and
trying to stop us doing it.

00:48:07.990 --> 00:48:10.194
So that's been a bit of
a hurdle to get over.

00:48:10.194 --> 00:48:12.360
And then the question of
the mitochondrial donation,

00:48:12.360 --> 00:48:14.550
as well, has been well debated.

00:48:14.550 --> 00:48:16.300
I've put in the
social-science literatures

00:48:16.300 --> 00:48:17.840
there, because it
had been a field

00:48:17.840 --> 00:48:21.640
day for social scientists,
over the past 10 years or so.

00:48:21.640 --> 00:48:26.030
I find myself the subject of
PhD theses of social scientists.

00:48:26.030 --> 00:48:29.680
So we're feeding a whole
different academic discipline.

00:48:32.490 --> 00:48:35.090
Very briefly, though, in terms
of altruistic egg-donation

00:48:35.090 --> 00:48:36.304
for research.

00:48:36.304 --> 00:48:38.470
These are two documents
that you can go and look at,

00:48:38.470 --> 00:48:40.570
if you want more
details about it.

00:48:40.570 --> 00:48:44.160
The HFEA did a report in 2006,
which we call the SEED Report.

00:48:44.160 --> 00:48:46.890
Now that was the donation
of sperm and eggs

00:48:46.890 --> 00:48:48.552
for clinical treatment.

00:48:48.552 --> 00:48:51.010
But it was a year later that
they went back and said, well,

00:48:51.010 --> 00:48:53.344
if we're going to allow
eggs and sperm to be donated

00:48:53.344 --> 00:48:55.010
for treatment, why
shouldn't we actually

00:48:55.010 --> 00:48:56.260
do it for research, as well?

00:48:56.260 --> 00:48:58.640
That, we thought,
was a good idea.

00:48:58.640 --> 00:49:00.140
The bottom line of
their discussions

00:49:00.140 --> 00:49:03.620
also included the
question about payment.

00:49:03.620 --> 00:49:05.700
And they agreed
that we could pay

00:49:05.700 --> 00:49:11.890
up to 750 pounds per donation
to cover their expenses.

00:49:11.890 --> 00:49:14.262
The Nuffield
Council on Bioethics

00:49:14.262 --> 00:49:16.220
also looked at the question
about egg donation.

00:49:16.220 --> 00:49:18.010
They did a wider
study which looked

00:49:18.010 --> 00:49:19.875
at the whole question
about participation

00:49:19.875 --> 00:49:22.110
in medical research,
organ donation,

00:49:22.110 --> 00:49:24.070
the whole question about
medical parts being

00:49:24.070 --> 00:49:27.550
used for clinical
practice and for donation.

00:49:27.550 --> 00:49:30.430
But they include a chapter
on eggs for research,

00:49:30.430 --> 00:49:33.110
as well, because it was
very topical at the time.

00:49:33.110 --> 00:49:34.700
And basically they're
saying that they

00:49:34.700 --> 00:49:35.820
didn't think there was
going to be a problem

00:49:35.820 --> 00:49:37.819
Why should it be regarded
as anything different?

00:49:37.819 --> 00:49:39.800
The use of the eggs
might be contentious,

00:49:39.800 --> 00:49:41.430
But the actual
process of donation,

00:49:41.430 --> 00:49:44.510
if the women wanted to
donate, was no more ethically

00:49:44.510 --> 00:49:47.125
challenging than any
other participation

00:49:47.125 --> 00:49:48.185
in medical research.

00:49:51.276 --> 00:49:53.900
The Nuffield Council also looked
at the mitochondrial transfer.

00:49:53.900 --> 00:49:55.890
And this is why I should
declare an interest.

00:49:55.890 --> 00:49:58.760
Because I was actually on the
Nuffield Council at this time.

00:49:58.760 --> 00:50:01.740
But I didn't have any part to
play in their deliberations.

00:50:01.740 --> 00:50:03.180
I actually left
the room whenever

00:50:03.180 --> 00:50:05.550
this particular
document was discussed.

00:50:05.550 --> 00:50:06.910
It's a very detailed document.

00:50:06.910 --> 00:50:09.724
And those of you that are
interested in the ethical issue

00:50:09.724 --> 00:50:10.640
should go and read it.

00:50:10.640 --> 00:50:18.180
I just picked out four parts,
just to go through in outline.

00:50:18.180 --> 00:50:19.890
Initially, I think,
people thought

00:50:19.890 --> 00:50:22.376
we were trying to deny that
it was germ-line therapy.

00:50:22.376 --> 00:50:23.750
But that was never
the intention.

00:50:23.750 --> 00:50:26.083
And we were always very clear,
right from the beginning,

00:50:26.083 --> 00:50:27.760
this is germ-line therapy.

00:50:27.760 --> 00:50:31.720
There is no point in removing
the mitochondria for a woman

00:50:31.720 --> 00:50:33.570
so she can be
healthy but passing

00:50:33.570 --> 00:50:35.680
the same risk on to her child.

00:50:35.680 --> 00:50:38.610
And, in fact, germ-line therapy,
in this particular case,

00:50:38.610 --> 00:50:40.660
is exactly what we want.

00:50:40.660 --> 00:50:42.890
Got into some difficulty--
some people suggesting,

00:50:42.890 --> 00:50:47.862
well, why don't we then do PGD
and only put back male fetuses,

00:50:47.862 --> 00:50:49.320
because the male
fetus is not going

00:50:49.320 --> 00:50:51.674
to pass on that mitochondria
to the next line?

00:50:51.674 --> 00:50:54.090
Well, hang on-- that's a bit
of sex discrimination, there.

00:50:54.090 --> 00:50:55.450
We can't have that.

00:50:55.450 --> 00:50:58.340
But there's a nice
debate about that.

00:50:58.340 --> 00:51:01.650
There's the whole ethical
issues about doing procedures

00:51:01.650 --> 00:51:05.565
that are basically experimenting
on a child that's unborn

00:51:05.565 --> 00:51:06.940
and what the rights
of that child

00:51:06.940 --> 00:51:10.870
might have to have any
say in what's being done.

00:51:10.870 --> 00:51:13.000
One of the issues
that's different here

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:16.320
than the sort of things
become challenging with IVF

00:51:16.320 --> 00:51:19.110
and infertility is
it this is a child

00:51:19.110 --> 00:51:22.410
that is likely to be born with
a very high risk of having

00:51:22.410 --> 00:51:24.930
a serious medical problem.

00:51:24.930 --> 00:51:27.270
And what we're doing
with these techniques

00:51:27.270 --> 00:51:29.322
is reducing the risk.

00:51:29.322 --> 00:51:31.405
It is absolutely true that
this child is not being

00:51:31.405 --> 00:51:32.854
given any choice in the matter.

00:51:32.854 --> 00:51:35.270
But I think we have to take a
little bit of responsibility

00:51:35.270 --> 00:51:37.170
for doing our best
to try and reduce

00:51:37.170 --> 00:51:41.980
the chance, as far of possible,
that that child will be OK.

00:51:41.980 --> 00:51:45.270
There was a lot of debate about
mitochondrial DNA and identity.

00:51:45.270 --> 00:51:48.600
Clearly it doesn't produce
the same identity issues

00:51:48.600 --> 00:51:51.430
as the nuclear DNA does.

00:51:51.430 --> 00:51:54.300
There was discussion
about whether,

00:51:54.300 --> 00:51:55.909
if you have an
abnormality of your DNA

00:51:55.909 --> 00:51:57.450
that makes you ill,
then that illness

00:51:57.450 --> 00:51:59.194
is part of your identity.

00:51:59.194 --> 00:52:00.860
We get slight mixed
messages about that.

00:52:00.860 --> 00:52:04.867
Why would we try and cure
anybody, if that were the case?

00:52:04.867 --> 00:52:06.950
The state of the mitochondrial
donor-- big debate,

00:52:06.950 --> 00:52:09.370
and a very important
debate, because it's

00:52:09.370 --> 00:52:11.900
going to depend on what
relationship, then,

00:52:11.900 --> 00:52:14.740
the mitochondrial
donor would have

00:52:14.740 --> 00:52:17.070
with any child or any family
that might be conceived,

00:52:17.070 --> 00:52:20.160
as a result. There's
two arguments.

00:52:20.160 --> 00:52:22.574
One what was that you can
say the mitochondrial donor

00:52:22.574 --> 00:52:23.740
is the same as an egg donor.

00:52:23.740 --> 00:52:25.240
So an egg or a sperm
donor, in order

00:52:25.240 --> 00:52:31.060
to have a child, in the UK that
donor has to give their name

00:52:31.060 --> 00:52:33.620
and has to potentially allow
the child to contact them

00:52:33.620 --> 00:52:35.045
when that child's 18.

00:52:35.045 --> 00:52:37.890
That really restricts the
number of donors we get.

00:52:37.890 --> 00:52:41.080
Alternatively, you could think
of the mitochondrial donor

00:52:41.080 --> 00:52:44.295
as being someone like a
blood donor-- an organ donor.

00:52:44.295 --> 00:52:46.951
And there are two different
ways of looking at it.

00:52:46.951 --> 00:52:48.450
Fortunately, the
way the regulations

00:52:48.450 --> 00:52:50.520
have come out because
of where I wanted

00:52:50.520 --> 00:52:53.620
it to be, they've come more down
the line of the blood donor,

00:52:53.620 --> 00:52:56.550
not the whole-egg donor.

00:52:56.550 --> 00:52:58.300
So our conclusion was
that, on balance, we

00:52:58.300 --> 00:52:59.860
believe that these
novel techniques,

00:52:59.860 --> 00:53:02.390
if they are adequately
proven to be acceptably

00:53:02.390 --> 00:53:04.320
safe and effective
as treatments,

00:53:04.320 --> 00:53:06.319
it would be ethical for
families to use them.

00:53:06.319 --> 00:53:07.860
And if they wish to
do, and have been

00:53:07.860 --> 00:53:10.330
offered an appropriate level
of information and support.

00:53:10.330 --> 00:53:15.060
And this particular document
that's came out was really

00:53:15.060 --> 00:53:18.510
helpful, when the debate came
in Parliament to say [? we ?]

00:53:18.510 --> 00:53:20.500
[? could ?] move ahead with it.

00:53:20.500 --> 00:53:25.590
So-- UK legislation.

00:53:25.590 --> 00:53:29.340
The act relating to what we
can do with human embryos,

00:53:29.340 --> 00:53:33.540
preimplantation, was in 1990.

00:53:33.540 --> 00:53:36.950
It's very good legislation,
because it gives us a good

00:53:36.950 --> 00:53:39.720
framework that says what
we can and we cannot do.

00:53:39.720 --> 00:53:41.826
And as long as we abide
by that legislation,

00:53:41.826 --> 00:53:42.700
we're going to be OK.

00:53:42.700 --> 00:53:45.230
I would have to say that the
way that it's implemented

00:53:45.230 --> 00:53:47.984
by the authority that regulates
is perhaps a little bit more

00:53:47.984 --> 00:53:49.150
robust than will be helpful.

00:53:52.030 --> 00:53:54.770
They needed to come
back to it later on,

00:53:54.770 --> 00:53:57.436
because the original
act of Parliament

00:53:57.436 --> 00:53:59.310
does allow us to do some
research on embryos,

00:53:59.310 --> 00:54:00.300
but it was restricted.

00:54:00.300 --> 00:54:01.900
So we could do
research to understand

00:54:01.900 --> 00:54:03.436
the cause of infertility.

00:54:03.436 --> 00:54:05.310
We could do research on
embryos to understand

00:54:05.310 --> 00:54:06.740
the cause of miscarriage.

00:54:06.740 --> 00:54:10.180
But once you start getting
into potential research

00:54:10.180 --> 00:54:12.940
to treat serious diseases
like mitochondria,

00:54:12.940 --> 00:54:14.470
it wasn't covered by the act.

00:54:14.470 --> 00:54:16.870
So they came and
revised it in 2001,

00:54:16.870 --> 00:54:20.030
so that then it was possible
to research on embryos

00:54:20.030 --> 00:54:22.330
for the purpose of
understanding the causes

00:54:22.330 --> 00:54:26.470
and developing treatments
for serious diseases.

00:54:26.470 --> 00:54:29.120
I've put in the
cloning act, there.

00:54:29.120 --> 00:54:31.472
There was a slight miswording
in the original act that

00:54:31.472 --> 00:54:34.584
meant potentially that
reproductive cloning could

00:54:34.584 --> 00:54:35.250
legal in the UK.

00:54:35.250 --> 00:54:37.208
They very quickly stopped
that, as soon as they

00:54:37.208 --> 00:54:39.190
realized that was a problem.

00:54:39.190 --> 00:54:41.450
We are not cloning.

00:54:41.450 --> 00:54:43.810
The act was revised
in 2008, because that

00:54:43.810 --> 00:54:46.024
was at the point at
which we were-- it was

00:54:46.024 --> 00:54:47.190
a routine review of the act.

00:54:47.190 --> 00:54:49.160
But we were saying
then, we're not that

00:54:49.160 --> 00:54:51.250
far away from being
able to come to you

00:54:51.250 --> 00:54:54.180
and say this is actually
someone we'd like to do.

00:54:54.180 --> 00:54:56.490
So the important thing
in the act in 2008

00:54:56.490 --> 00:54:59.290
was they put a clause in
that said we would not

00:54:59.290 --> 00:55:01.770
need to go back to
primary legislation

00:55:01.770 --> 00:55:04.140
in order to allow this to
become legal in the UK.

00:55:04.140 --> 00:55:07.290
It was still illegal,
under the act,

00:55:07.290 --> 00:55:09.940
but they said that we could go
back to the secretary of state

00:55:09.940 --> 00:55:11.360
and ask permission.

00:55:11.360 --> 00:55:13.290
And that would allow
us to get it through.

00:55:13.290 --> 00:55:17.340
But it would need to go back
to debate in Parliament.

00:55:17.340 --> 00:55:19.459
So the regulations
that were put together

00:55:19.459 --> 00:55:21.000
that will make this
something that we

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:23.360
can do-- these techniques
for nuclear transfer

00:55:23.360 --> 00:55:26.510
an spindle transfer-- make them
legally acceptable techniques

00:55:26.510 --> 00:55:27.670
were put to Parliament.

00:55:27.670 --> 00:55:31.060
They were debated and voted
in the House of Commons

00:55:31.060 --> 00:55:33.350
in February this year.

00:55:33.350 --> 00:55:36.150
Massive vote in favor.

00:55:36.150 --> 00:55:41.410
And then, in the House of Lords,
later in February, again, 208

00:55:41.410 --> 00:55:43.360
for and 48 against.

00:55:43.360 --> 00:55:45.070
It was pretty overwhelming.

00:55:45.070 --> 00:55:47.192
I was in the debate for
the House of Lords one.

00:55:47.192 --> 00:55:49.400
I'd never seen so many
members of the House of Lords,

00:55:49.400 --> 00:55:51.358
because usually they
sleep in the back benches.

00:55:51.358 --> 00:55:53.220
But it was very full.

00:55:53.220 --> 00:55:58.350
But even the bishops who
were there were abstaining--

00:55:58.350 --> 00:56:01.010
were saying, we're understanding
humanity-- what it was

00:56:01.010 --> 00:56:02.310
and what we were trying to do.

00:56:02.310 --> 00:56:04.050
I think the big
advantage in the UK

00:56:04.050 --> 00:56:06.710
this it's not a party
political issue.

00:56:06.710 --> 00:56:07.940
This was a free vote.

00:56:07.940 --> 00:56:09.740
It was based on
consciences alone,

00:56:09.740 --> 00:56:11.020
and that was very helpful.

00:56:11.020 --> 00:56:13.830
Issues related to reproduction
legislation in the UK

00:56:13.830 --> 00:56:17.430
has never been a
party political issue.

00:56:17.430 --> 00:56:22.337
So where we are now--
these procedures

00:56:22.337 --> 00:56:23.920
were passed by
Parliament in February.

00:56:23.920 --> 00:56:26.460
They will become the law
at the end of October.

00:56:26.460 --> 00:56:28.110
That means at that
point we can apply

00:56:28.110 --> 00:56:30.040
to be the HFEA for a license.

00:56:30.040 --> 00:56:31.590
At that point, the
scientific data

00:56:31.590 --> 00:56:33.820
will be reviewed by the HFEA.

00:56:33.820 --> 00:56:36.004
And if they say that
we have provided

00:56:36.004 --> 00:56:37.420
the evidence as
necessary, we hope

00:56:37.420 --> 00:56:38.628
we'll get a license to do it.

00:56:38.628 --> 00:56:40.390
So we could be in
a position to be

00:56:40.390 --> 00:56:43.646
able to offer this in treatment
within the next few months.

00:56:43.646 --> 00:56:46.020
I'm going to give you just a
little bit about the science

00:56:46.020 --> 00:56:46.645
where they are.

00:56:46.645 --> 00:56:50.040
Because, obviously, the
science is developing.

00:56:50.040 --> 00:56:52.580
We're getting 92% oocytes
surviving the pronuclear

00:56:52.580 --> 00:56:53.600
transfer procedure.

00:56:53.600 --> 00:56:56.370
And the blastocycte development
right now has gone up to 54%.

00:56:56.370 --> 00:56:57.911
Louise is really
green-fingerprinting

00:56:57.911 --> 00:56:58.870
these techniques.

00:56:58.870 --> 00:57:00.930
Obviously the data
that's really important

00:57:00.930 --> 00:57:03.957
is looking at the carryover,
looking at the chromosomes,

00:57:03.957 --> 00:57:05.790
looking at stem cells
that have been derived

00:57:05.790 --> 00:57:07.130
and what the deal is.

00:57:07.130 --> 00:57:08.588
I'm not going to
give you this now,

00:57:08.588 --> 00:57:10.760
because it's too
politically sensitive,

00:57:10.760 --> 00:57:12.260
and it's not
appropriate to give you

00:57:12.260 --> 00:57:14.301
that sort of scientific
data before it's actually

00:57:14.301 --> 00:57:16.870
formally gone to peer review.

00:57:16.870 --> 00:57:19.080
Mary Herbert, who's the
scientist that leads this,

00:57:19.080 --> 00:57:20.770
is a very good scientist.

00:57:20.770 --> 00:57:23.250
She's very careful, and
she's very cautious.

00:57:23.250 --> 00:57:26.010
Her team is small,
but it's really good.

00:57:26.010 --> 00:57:27.850
The way that the
science has developed

00:57:27.850 --> 00:57:31.050
in this particular
area of procedures

00:57:31.050 --> 00:57:32.940
has to be slightly different.

00:57:32.940 --> 00:57:35.380
It's not any good
to be the "I want

00:57:35.380 --> 00:57:37.970
to be the first in Nature
for the publication"

00:57:37.970 --> 00:57:40.240
and then get it wrong
and make a mistake.

00:57:40.240 --> 00:57:42.461
What we need to do is
to be absolutely sure

00:57:42.461 --> 00:57:43.960
that, when we get
it published, it's

00:57:43.960 --> 00:57:46.450
as good as it's going
to be, it's robust,

00:57:46.450 --> 00:57:49.070
and that will give us
the safety of issues

00:57:49.070 --> 00:57:53.070
that we need to have
to make it work.

00:57:53.070 --> 00:57:55.447
So these are the
scientists that were here.

00:57:55.447 --> 00:57:57.280
Now, obviously, there
have been an awful lot

00:57:57.280 --> 00:57:59.030
of other people
who've been involved,

00:57:59.030 --> 00:58:01.850
talking about the ethics,
the lobbying, the politics.

00:58:01.850 --> 00:58:05.160
But I'm going to pick out just
one group on my final slide,

00:58:05.160 --> 00:58:07.780
just to say.

00:58:07.780 --> 00:58:11.220
The Lily Foundation
was an organization

00:58:11.220 --> 00:58:14.890
that was set up
by Lily's parents

00:58:14.890 --> 00:58:18.430
to support research and develop
treatments to help prevent

00:58:18.430 --> 00:58:19.650
mitochondrial disease.

00:58:19.650 --> 00:58:22.110
Lily died at the age
of eight months old

00:58:22.110 --> 00:58:24.520
from mitochondrial disease.

00:58:24.520 --> 00:58:27.960
It was Lily's parents, and
like her who went to the press.

00:58:27.960 --> 00:58:30.620
They went on the radio,
they went to the newspapers,

00:58:30.620 --> 00:58:32.680
and told their stories.

00:58:32.680 --> 00:58:35.562
They took their babies
into the television studios

00:58:35.562 --> 00:58:37.020
and showed them to
people and said,

00:58:37.020 --> 00:58:40.090
my baby's going to die
in a few months' time.

00:58:40.090 --> 00:58:41.675
And really that
was the thing that

00:58:41.675 --> 00:58:44.720
was most powerful in getting
it to the stage in the UK

00:58:44.720 --> 00:58:46.500
that it is now.

00:58:46.500 --> 00:58:48.050
I think Lily won, in the end.

00:58:48.050 --> 00:58:49.418
Thank you.

