00:59:50.160 --> 00:59:50.660
So, hi.

00:59:50.660 --> 00:59:52.344
So my name's Floyd Romesberg.

00:59:52.344 --> 00:59:54.010
It's a real pleasure
to come to tell you

00:59:54.010 --> 00:59:55.593
about some of the
research in my group

00:59:55.593 --> 00:59:57.040
at the Scripps
Research Institute.

00:59:57.040 --> 00:59:58.664
So fundamentally what
I'm interested in

00:59:58.664 --> 01:00:01.000
and what my group works
on are different aspects

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:03.474
of thinking about
evolution and applying it.

01:00:03.474 --> 01:00:05.640
And it's all from a very
much chemist's perspective.

01:00:05.640 --> 01:00:07.830
I'm a chemist by training.

01:00:07.830 --> 01:00:10.210
And so what I'm so what the
project's largely focused on

01:00:10.210 --> 01:00:12.560
are trying to develop--
use concepts from evolution

01:00:12.560 --> 01:00:14.940
to develop novel approaches
to antibiotics discovery,

01:00:14.940 --> 01:00:16.850
biophysical characterization,
to understand

01:00:16.850 --> 01:00:18.225
the process of evolution.

01:00:18.225 --> 01:00:20.100
And what I'm going to
talk to you about today

01:00:20.100 --> 01:00:22.900
is an attempt to expand
the genetic alphabet--

01:00:22.900 --> 01:00:27.250
to augment the potential of
what evolution can do so.

01:00:27.250 --> 01:00:29.527
So the project, especially
in its early days,

01:00:29.527 --> 01:00:31.860
was focused very much on
expanding the genetic alphabet.

01:00:31.860 --> 01:00:33.000
So there it is.

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:35.300
That's the genetic
alphabet of E. coli.

01:00:35.300 --> 01:00:38.170
If you can't see it, let
me blow it up for you.

01:00:38.170 --> 01:00:40.394
So I gave this talk in
China, about a year ago.

01:00:40.394 --> 01:00:42.310
And someone came up to
me afterwards and said,

01:00:42.310 --> 01:00:43.050
you know, you have
a lot of nerve,

01:00:43.050 --> 01:00:45.035
showing the Japanese
flag in China.

01:00:45.035 --> 01:00:46.310
[LAUGHTER]

01:00:46.310 --> 01:00:47.130
But anyway.

01:00:47.130 --> 01:00:49.360
So the genetic alphabet
in all organisms-- and I

01:00:49.360 --> 01:00:50.690
could've told you-- I
mean, this is E. coli,

01:00:50.690 --> 01:00:52.270
but it looks pretty
much the same.

01:00:52.270 --> 01:00:55.560
It's just long strings
of Gs, Cs, As, and Ts.

01:00:55.560 --> 01:01:00.040
And Gs pair with C,
and As pair with T.

01:01:00.040 --> 01:01:04.170
And that's the mechanism
of replication and storage

01:01:04.170 --> 01:01:06.200
and retrieval of
genetic information.

01:01:06.200 --> 01:01:09.510
And so, if one were
interested in expanding that,

01:01:09.510 --> 01:01:10.889
to create an
organism that stored

01:01:10.889 --> 01:01:12.930
more information-- eventually
could retrieve more

01:01:12.930 --> 01:01:15.100
information-- such
a semisynthetic cell

01:01:15.100 --> 01:01:16.805
might look something like this.

01:01:16.805 --> 01:01:18.180
There's a variety
of things you'd

01:01:18.180 --> 01:01:19.305
have to be concerned about.

01:01:19.305 --> 01:01:21.200
You'd have to have your
unnatural nucleotide.

01:01:21.200 --> 01:01:23.490
So you'd have to have a
third pair of nucleotides.

01:01:23.490 --> 01:01:25.749
So G, C, A, and T
are all nucleotides.

01:01:25.749 --> 01:01:27.790
You'd have to have nucleotide
X and nucleotide Y.

01:01:27.790 --> 01:01:29.982
And X and Y would have
to pair with each other.

01:01:29.982 --> 01:01:31.940
So, for example, if you
had Y in a piece of DNA

01:01:31.940 --> 01:01:33.650
during DNA
replication, you'd have

01:01:33.650 --> 01:01:35.966
to have the correct
triphosphate that's

01:01:35.966 --> 01:01:37.465
the activated form
of the nucleoside

01:01:37.465 --> 01:01:39.420
that the polymerase needs.

01:01:39.420 --> 01:01:41.310
You'd have to have that
polymerase faithfully

01:01:41.310 --> 01:01:43.414
and with high
efficiency recognize

01:01:43.414 --> 01:01:45.080
the unnatural nucleotide
in the template

01:01:45.080 --> 01:01:48.280
and put in its cognate
pair in the growing strand,

01:01:48.280 --> 01:01:49.734
during replication.

01:01:49.734 --> 01:01:52.150
And then, of course, you'd
have to have an RNA polymerase.

01:01:52.150 --> 01:01:54.884
You'd have to have the requisite
triphosphates available

01:01:54.884 --> 01:01:55.550
within the cell.

01:01:55.550 --> 01:01:57.341
You'd have to have an
RNA polymerase, then,

01:01:57.341 --> 01:01:59.880
that recognizes
templates containing

01:01:59.880 --> 01:02:01.525
DNA genes-- for
example, containing

01:02:01.525 --> 01:02:04.221
the unnatural nucleotide--
to produce RNA strands that

01:02:04.221 --> 01:02:06.720
contain the unnatural nucleotide
which would go out and find

01:02:06.720 --> 01:02:10.390
the ribosome and
maybe direct tRNA--

01:02:10.390 --> 01:02:12.760
the ribosomes-- to synthesize
proteins containing

01:02:12.760 --> 01:02:13.740
unnatural amino acids.

01:02:13.740 --> 01:02:16.540
So I don't have a lot of
time to tell you about what

01:02:16.540 --> 01:02:18.921
our interest and why we're
so interested in eventually

01:02:18.921 --> 01:02:20.670
getting to the state
of producing proteins

01:02:20.670 --> 01:02:21.875
with unnatural amino acids.

01:02:21.875 --> 01:02:24.000
But suffice it to say that
protein therapeutics are

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:26.400
a big deal, despite
having really

01:02:26.400 --> 01:02:28.887
limited chemical functionality
available within them.

01:02:28.887 --> 01:02:31.220
And if one could expand the
scope of what proteins could

01:02:31.220 --> 01:02:33.864
be made, maybe even
in evolvable context,

01:02:33.864 --> 01:02:35.780
one could imagine
developing therapeutics that

01:02:35.780 --> 01:02:38.630
really revolutionize medicine.

01:02:38.630 --> 01:02:41.089
So at this point I do want to
acknowledge the seminal work

01:02:41.089 --> 01:02:41.880
of a couple people.

01:02:41.880 --> 01:02:47.350
Peter Schultz, who has worked
with recoding an amber codon.

01:02:47.350 --> 01:02:50.675
So, of the 64
possible codons that

01:02:50.675 --> 01:02:52.860
are available in natural
DNA, three of them

01:02:52.860 --> 01:02:54.520
are reserved as stop signals.

01:02:54.520 --> 01:02:56.600
And Pete was clever
enough to figure out

01:02:56.600 --> 01:03:00.550
how to take one of those
and have it recognized

01:03:00.550 --> 01:03:04.360
by an unnatural-- a tRNA from
a different organism that

01:03:04.360 --> 01:03:07.360
was charged by an enzyme
that charges tRNAs

01:03:07.360 --> 01:03:08.730
with an unnatural amino acid.

01:03:08.730 --> 01:03:11.146
And he a couple of those that
work really want in E. coli.

01:03:11.146 --> 01:03:14.160
And partly I'm acknowledging
him because we plan fully

01:03:14.160 --> 01:03:17.450
on stealing those tRNAs.

01:03:17.450 --> 01:03:21.350
And, instead of recoding
for them with stop codons,

01:03:21.350 --> 01:03:24.260
the idea is to generate
with unnatural nucleotides,

01:03:24.260 --> 01:03:26.320
essentially, an infinite
number of new codons

01:03:26.320 --> 01:03:29.056
that you could use to encode
for unnatural amino acids.

01:03:29.056 --> 01:03:30.680
And the second person
I want to mention

01:03:30.680 --> 01:03:32.770
is Steve Benner, who was
the first to popularize

01:03:32.770 --> 01:03:34.690
the idea of developing
unnatural nucleotides.

01:03:34.690 --> 01:03:36.250
And the way Steve
did it was he said,

01:03:36.250 --> 01:03:40.155
look-- G-C and A-T sort of
pair in a complementary way,

01:03:40.155 --> 01:03:42.030
based on something called
"hydrogen bonding."

01:03:42.030 --> 01:03:45.000
So you have a hydrogen donor
here, and an acceptor here,

01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:46.030
and that's sticky.

01:03:46.030 --> 01:03:48.020
That's water-like.

01:03:48.020 --> 01:03:49.614
And he worked for years.

01:03:49.614 --> 01:03:51.280
And he's made a lot
of progress, lately.

01:03:51.280 --> 01:03:52.970
But one of the
problems that he had

01:03:52.970 --> 01:03:55.430
was that those hydrogen-bonding
patterns could scramble.

01:03:55.430 --> 01:03:58.380
And because natural G, C, A,
and T recognize each other

01:03:58.380 --> 01:04:01.909
based on similar sorts of
hydrogen-bonding patterns,

01:04:01.909 --> 01:04:03.200
it was a real fidelity problem.

01:04:03.200 --> 01:04:04.850
So his unnatural
nucleotides would

01:04:04.850 --> 01:04:06.640
mis-pair with the natural ones.

01:04:06.640 --> 01:04:08.321
So the approach that
we took-- I want

01:04:08.321 --> 01:04:09.570
to give you a couple examples.

01:04:09.570 --> 01:04:11.611
Now there's way more
information here than I want

01:04:11.611 --> 01:04:13.890
you to absorb in any detail.

01:04:13.890 --> 01:04:16.140
So, first of all,
what I'm showing here

01:04:16.140 --> 01:04:18.110
is the nucleobase
of the nucleotides.

01:04:18.110 --> 01:04:20.240
So this is the part that
pairs with each other.

01:04:20.240 --> 01:04:22.870
The rest of the nucleotide
has a little sugar, down here,

01:04:22.870 --> 01:04:24.070
and maybe a phosphate.

01:04:24.070 --> 01:04:26.080
And I'm ignoring
those, for simplicity.

01:04:26.080 --> 01:04:27.580
The synthetic
chemists in my lab who

01:04:27.580 --> 01:04:29.400
slave away for
years, making these,

01:04:29.400 --> 01:04:33.240
love me reducing
them to this little--

01:04:33.240 --> 01:04:34.950
So one thing I want
to mention about this

01:04:34.950 --> 01:04:36.658
is that we did not
take Steve's approach.

01:04:36.658 --> 01:04:38.880
We took up-- these are
all hydrophobic, oily,

01:04:38.880 --> 01:04:39.850
greasy-looking.

01:04:39.850 --> 01:04:42.361
So everyone knows that
water and oil don't mix.

01:04:42.361 --> 01:04:44.110
So that's called the
"hydrophobic effect."

01:04:44.110 --> 01:04:45.866
Partly that's the
hydrophobic effect.

01:04:45.866 --> 01:04:47.240
Water and oil
exclude each other.

01:04:47.240 --> 01:04:49.600
Water likes to be with water,
and oil likes to be with oil.

01:04:49.600 --> 01:04:51.683
So we thought, if we make
hydrophobic nucleobases,

01:04:51.683 --> 01:04:53.380
maybe they'll pair
with each other

01:04:53.380 --> 01:04:55.680
and avoid the more
water-like nucleobases.

01:04:55.680 --> 01:04:58.660
And maybe we can start with
greater orthogonality-- greater

01:04:58.660 --> 01:05:01.070
ability to not mis-pair with
the natural nucleotides.

01:05:01.070 --> 01:05:02.140
So that's one thing about these.

01:05:02.140 --> 01:05:02.930
These are all hydrophobic.

01:05:02.930 --> 01:05:04.555
They're also large,
because we thought,

01:05:04.555 --> 01:05:06.779
heck-- you know, we're taking
the hydrogen bonds out.

01:05:06.779 --> 01:05:08.820
What else is going to
stabilize the DNA, if we've

01:05:08.820 --> 01:05:09.986
taken the hydrogen ones out?

01:05:09.986 --> 01:05:12.550
So we need large
surface area to pair

01:05:12.550 --> 01:05:15.431
within a strand of that
double-strand, duplex DNA,

01:05:15.431 --> 01:05:16.180
to make it stable.

01:05:16.180 --> 01:05:17.935
So that's one thing-- they're
all large and hydrophobic--

01:05:17.935 --> 01:05:18.760
that I want to point out.

01:05:18.760 --> 01:05:20.799
And the second thing
about the approach we took

01:05:20.799 --> 01:05:22.590
is that we didn't take
the traditional sort

01:05:22.590 --> 01:05:26.290
of biorganic chemists' approach,
where we make something,

01:05:26.290 --> 01:05:29.265
design it very carefully,
maybe, make it, and then spend

01:05:29.265 --> 01:05:30.690
a year studying it.

01:05:30.690 --> 01:05:32.580
We took a
medicinal-chemistry approach,

01:05:32.580 --> 01:05:35.480
where we made lots of
analogs, we analyzed them

01:05:35.480 --> 01:05:37.660
with assays that were
very fast, and then

01:05:37.660 --> 01:05:39.560
we could evaluate
changes that we made

01:05:39.560 --> 01:05:42.830
and build structure activity
relationships-- SARs-- just

01:05:42.830 --> 01:05:44.350
like medicinal chemists do.

01:05:44.350 --> 01:05:47.090
I'm a huge fan of
medicinal chemists.

01:05:47.090 --> 01:05:50.110
And, in that way, optimize
the unnatural base pair.

01:05:50.110 --> 01:05:52.830
So the sorts of assays
is not real important.

01:05:52.830 --> 01:05:54.590
But we measure the
temperature at which

01:05:54.590 --> 01:05:55.830
the duplex falls apart.

01:05:55.830 --> 01:05:57.890
That gives you a
measure of stability.

01:05:57.890 --> 01:05:59.690
So we put the different
unnatural pairs

01:05:59.690 --> 01:06:01.560
within the duplex and
measured stability.

01:06:01.560 --> 01:06:04.330
And then the real key
SAR came out of kinetics.

01:06:04.330 --> 01:06:08.000
We take a DNA primer-- a
template that has the unnatural

01:06:08.000 --> 01:06:11.230
nucleotide ready to direct the
incorporation of its correct

01:06:11.230 --> 01:06:13.540
triphosphate, as I mentioned--
and then we add a DNA

01:06:13.540 --> 01:06:16.130
polymerase and measure how
quickly and efficiently it can

01:06:16.130 --> 01:06:18.570
do that, relative to
potential mis-pairs..

01:06:18.570 --> 01:06:19.521
Now there's two steps.

01:06:19.521 --> 01:06:20.770
There's an incorporation step.

01:06:20.770 --> 01:06:21.880
That's the step where
you actually pull

01:06:21.880 --> 01:06:24.250
the unnatural nucleobase
out of solution-- unnatural

01:06:24.250 --> 01:06:26.680
nucelotide-- and
covalently attach it

01:06:26.680 --> 01:06:28.070
to this primer terminus.

01:06:28.070 --> 01:06:30.200
But now the primer
terminus is unnatural.

01:06:30.200 --> 01:06:32.930
So the next step of maybe
adding the next correct, natural

01:06:32.930 --> 01:06:34.050
nucleotide is different.

01:06:34.050 --> 01:06:35.845
So we call that the
"extension" step.

01:06:35.845 --> 01:06:37.595
So we evaluate both
of them independently.

01:06:37.595 --> 01:06:41.989
The incorporation step
wound up-- in retrospect,

01:06:41.989 --> 01:06:44.030
we wound up sort of
referring to this first group

01:06:44.030 --> 01:06:45.740
of unnatural
nucleobases' nucleotides

01:06:45.740 --> 01:06:47.840
as our first-generation analogs.

01:06:47.840 --> 01:06:49.960
And the SAR that
really came out of that

01:06:49.960 --> 01:06:52.640
was that those analogs--
we could optimize them

01:06:52.640 --> 01:06:55.230
for that incorporation
step to be very efficient.

01:06:55.230 --> 01:06:57.890
What became the real challenge
was optimizing this extension

01:06:57.890 --> 01:06:58.840
step.

01:06:58.840 --> 01:07:00.520
That became the
biggest challenge.

01:07:00.520 --> 01:07:04.497
So we solved a structure
of one of the better

01:07:04.497 --> 01:07:06.580
of the first-generation
analogs, and that was just

01:07:06.580 --> 01:07:07.947
this propinal isocarbostyril.

01:07:07.947 --> 01:07:10.030
It's kind of a joke, in
my lab, how we name these.

01:07:10.030 --> 01:07:11.820
Because we tried to
be very systematic,

01:07:11.820 --> 01:07:14.290
at first, but we've
synthesized about 250.

01:07:14.290 --> 01:07:16.260
And you just run out of names.

01:07:16.260 --> 01:07:20.330
So we solved the structure
of DNA containing this.

01:07:20.330 --> 01:07:22.970
And we solved it with Dave
Wemmer at Berkeley and Pete

01:07:22.970 --> 01:07:24.426
Schultz at Scripps.

01:07:24.426 --> 01:07:25.050
And here it is.

01:07:25.050 --> 01:07:26.160
So here's a piece of duplex DNA.

01:07:26.160 --> 01:07:28.050
Here's our little pair,
stuck in the middle.

01:07:28.050 --> 01:07:29.960
And you see it doesn't look
like a Watson-Crick pair.

01:07:29.960 --> 01:07:31.900
So all these other
pairs-- these G-C pairs--

01:07:31.900 --> 01:07:35.450
these famous rungs of the
ladder-- didn't look like that.

01:07:35.450 --> 01:07:37.010
It looks like this.

01:07:37.010 --> 01:07:39.189
They cross-strand
intercalate, because they're

01:07:39.189 --> 01:07:40.980
big and hydrophobic
and greasy, and they're

01:07:40.980 --> 01:07:42.341
grabbing onto each other.

01:07:42.341 --> 01:07:43.840
And maybe that
doesn't surprise you,

01:07:43.840 --> 01:07:46.131
because we didn't design
these to pair with each other.

01:07:46.131 --> 01:07:49.170
This just came out of the SAR.

01:07:49.170 --> 01:07:50.610
But in our mind's
eye, we thought

01:07:50.610 --> 01:07:53.720
that this explained that
SAR that I just described.

01:07:53.720 --> 01:07:57.780
So if you imagine this same
modality of interaction

01:07:57.780 --> 01:08:00.480
is occurring during replication
in a polymerase-active site--

01:08:00.480 --> 01:08:01.970
let's say this is
a template, this

01:08:01.970 --> 01:08:03.530
is a growing primer strand.

01:08:03.530 --> 01:08:05.160
As you add this
unnatural nucleotide,

01:08:05.160 --> 01:08:09.270
it's going to reach out and
intercalate into its-- reach

01:08:09.270 --> 01:08:10.650
into its opposite strand.

01:08:10.650 --> 01:08:14.030
And most of the distortion that
comes with that pinching down,

01:08:14.030 --> 01:08:17.790
for this to happen, is going
to be absorbed by the primer

01:08:17.790 --> 01:08:20.920
terminus, because it's less
locked down by the polymerase.

01:08:20.920 --> 01:08:22.041
It's more free to move.

01:08:22.041 --> 01:08:24.499
So that's why it synthesized
well, because it's getting out

01:08:24.499 --> 01:08:24.950
of water.

01:08:24.950 --> 01:08:26.000
It doesn't like being in water.

01:08:26.000 --> 01:08:26.620
It's hydrophobic.

01:08:26.620 --> 01:08:28.250
It's getting to this beautiful
hydrophobic environment

01:08:28.250 --> 01:08:30.895
that it loves, but now it has
a distorted primer terminus,

01:08:30.895 --> 01:08:32.257
and it can't go on.

01:08:32.257 --> 01:08:33.840
So we thought that
explained the data.

01:08:33.840 --> 01:08:36.340
So, in what became known as our
"second-generation analogs,"

01:08:36.340 --> 01:08:38.010
we made smaller analogs.

01:08:38.010 --> 01:08:40.130
And we said, look-- the
incorporation step was

01:08:40.130 --> 01:08:42.120
so subject to
optimization, maybe

01:08:42.120 --> 01:08:45.500
we can make smaller analogs that
are less prone to intercalate

01:08:45.500 --> 01:08:48.540
and optimize the incorporation
step anyway, and then

01:08:48.540 --> 01:08:52.399
be in a better position to
optimize extension, as well.

01:08:52.399 --> 01:08:53.255
This kind of worked.

01:08:53.255 --> 01:08:55.505
And I don't have a lot of
time to explain this to you,

01:08:55.505 --> 01:08:56.630
because there's a subtlety.

01:08:56.630 --> 01:08:58.850
But there was a real
contradiction in the SAR.

01:08:58.850 --> 01:09:02.200
And that was, it had to do with
the nature of the substituent

01:09:02.200 --> 01:09:03.080
that I've shown here.

01:09:03.080 --> 01:09:05.100
So chemists would call
this the "ortho position"

01:09:05.100 --> 01:09:06.630
to the glycosidic bond.

01:09:06.630 --> 01:09:09.069
The "glycosidic bond" is just
a name for the sugar bond.

01:09:09.069 --> 01:09:10.569
So this is the sugar bond.

01:09:10.569 --> 01:09:13.979
And so it's this position
I've noted, there.

01:09:13.979 --> 01:09:16.890
In order for the insertion
step to be efficient,

01:09:16.890 --> 01:09:19.510
whenever the nucleobase--
the unnatural nucleotide

01:09:19.510 --> 01:09:21.830
is in the template or is
the incoming triphosphate,

01:09:21.830 --> 01:09:25.500
you want that substituent
to be hydrophobic-- greasy.

01:09:25.500 --> 01:09:28.452
But when it comes to the next
step, the extension step,

01:09:28.452 --> 01:09:29.910
you still want it
to be hydrophobic

01:09:29.910 --> 01:09:31.439
when it's in the
template, but when

01:09:31.439 --> 01:09:34.130
it's in the primer terminus
you need it to be hydrophilic.

01:09:34.130 --> 01:09:35.569
You need it to accept an H bond.

01:09:35.569 --> 01:09:37.300
And for those
polymerase aficionados

01:09:37.300 --> 01:09:39.870
in the audience-- I know
there are a couple of you--

01:09:39.870 --> 01:09:41.979
it's because the polymerase
is donating an H bond.

01:09:41.979 --> 01:09:44.609
It needs to interact in
an H-bonding-like way

01:09:44.609 --> 01:09:45.870
with that primer terminus.

01:09:45.870 --> 01:09:47.359
So it's not an
H-bond interaction

01:09:47.359 --> 01:09:49.310
between the nucleobases,
it's an H bond

01:09:49.310 --> 01:09:52.359
between the growing primer
terminus and the polymerase.

01:09:52.359 --> 01:09:55.282
So we were kind of stuck,
because that's a contradiction.

01:09:55.282 --> 01:09:57.490
How do you make an analog
that's both hydrophobic and

01:09:57.490 --> 01:09:59.050
hydrophilic simultaneously?

01:09:59.050 --> 01:10:01.820
So we ran a couple of
independent screens

01:10:01.820 --> 01:10:04.340
where we screened through
over almost 2,000 candidate

01:10:04.340 --> 01:10:05.890
unnatural base pairs.

01:10:05.890 --> 01:10:07.670
They were independent screens.

01:10:07.670 --> 01:10:09.910
And the only important point
is they both identified

01:10:09.910 --> 01:10:13.450
the very same pair-- a
first-generation analog,

01:10:13.450 --> 01:10:15.440
and a second-generation analog.

01:10:15.440 --> 01:10:18.050
This was the second of a series
of methyl methoxy derivatives,

01:10:18.050 --> 01:10:22.880
and this was this 5-methyl
sulfur isocarbostyril.

01:10:22.880 --> 01:10:25.470
And notice the nature
of these substituents.

01:10:25.470 --> 01:10:29.710
Sulfur is able to accept
a hydrogen bond but not

01:10:29.710 --> 01:10:31.990
as good as the oxygen.
But it's still able to.

01:10:31.990 --> 01:10:33.980
But it's much more
polarizable and hydrophobic.

01:10:33.980 --> 01:10:36.060
So it's a compromise.

01:10:36.060 --> 01:10:37.890
And O methyl is
just a bond rotation

01:10:37.890 --> 01:10:40.040
away from presenting
a hydrophobic surface

01:10:40.040 --> 01:10:41.260
versus an H-bonding surface.

01:10:41.260 --> 01:10:42.830
So, at least in
our mind's eye, we

01:10:42.830 --> 01:10:45.660
envisioned that was how that
SAR conflict was resolved.

01:10:45.660 --> 01:10:48.150
But this very much, very
quickly reinvigorated

01:10:48.150 --> 01:10:48.950
our design effort.

01:10:48.950 --> 01:10:52.740
And we optimized this pair
by filling in this ring,

01:10:52.740 --> 01:10:55.620
here, resulting in what we
called this naphthyl methoxy

01:10:55.620 --> 01:10:57.149
or NAM 5,6 pair.

01:10:57.149 --> 01:10:59.690
And a lot of what I'm going to
tell you about in this last 13

01:10:59.690 --> 01:11:03.020
minutes is work with this pair.

01:11:03.020 --> 01:11:06.620
Very recently, we've discovered
this analog of TPT5,6 called

01:11:06.620 --> 01:11:11.250
"TPT3," which replicates
better than this pair.

01:11:11.250 --> 01:11:14.030
In the early days, we
did a lot of kinetics.

01:11:14.030 --> 01:11:17.740
This pair replicates too well to
measure by kinetics-- too fast.

01:11:17.740 --> 01:11:19.720
So we use a sequencing method.

01:11:19.720 --> 01:11:23.260
So we submit the DNA to
the sequencing facility,

01:11:23.260 --> 01:11:25.181
using just standard
Sanger sequencing,

01:11:25.181 --> 01:11:27.180
where you don't have the
unnatural triphosphates

01:11:27.180 --> 01:11:27.720
present.

01:11:27.720 --> 01:11:30.590
You see an abrupt termination at
the spot of the unnatural base

01:11:30.590 --> 01:11:31.270
pair.

01:11:31.270 --> 01:11:35.230
And you can ratio the amplitudes
and get calibration curves

01:11:35.230 --> 01:11:36.640
to determine fidelities.

01:11:36.640 --> 01:11:38.440
We've done PCR amplifications.

01:11:38.440 --> 01:11:40.015
These are 150 more
pieces of DNA.

01:11:40.015 --> 01:11:42.140
And I'm only showing you
the local sequence context

01:11:42.140 --> 01:11:44.010
so that we can replicate
in a whole variety

01:11:44.010 --> 01:11:45.620
of different sequence
contexts, including

01:11:45.620 --> 01:11:46.890
sequence contexts where
the unnatural base

01:11:46.890 --> 01:11:48.540
pairs are next to each other.

01:11:48.540 --> 01:11:51.130
Now, really quick, I shouldn't
take the time to tell you this,

01:11:51.130 --> 01:11:52.046
but I love this story.

01:11:52.046 --> 01:11:55.100
This is maybe one my
favorite parts of the story.

01:11:55.100 --> 01:11:59.580
We solved the
structure of NAM5,6.

01:11:59.580 --> 01:12:01.896
And, lo and behold, it
was intercalated again.

01:12:01.896 --> 01:12:06.140
It was a real light-bulb
experience in my life.

01:12:06.140 --> 01:12:07.490
They're never going to do this.

01:12:07.490 --> 01:12:08.830
There's nothing to be
had-- there's nothing

01:12:08.830 --> 01:12:09.990
to be gotten from doing this.

01:12:09.990 --> 01:12:10.890
There's no H bonds there.

01:12:10.890 --> 01:12:12.598
They're going to do
whatever they can do,

01:12:12.598 --> 01:12:14.170
and that's intercalate.

01:12:14.170 --> 01:12:16.420
Now, if you go into a medicinal
chemist, and you said,

01:12:16.420 --> 01:12:18.500
look, we've got this molecule
with this great activity.

01:12:18.500 --> 01:12:19.530
It's a great antibiotic.

01:12:19.530 --> 01:12:21.446
And the medicinal chemist
will tell you, well,

01:12:21.446 --> 01:12:22.260
what's the target?

01:12:22.260 --> 01:12:23.210
And you'll say,
well, I don't know.

01:12:23.210 --> 01:12:23.782
Who cares?

01:12:23.782 --> 01:12:24.990
It's got this great activity.

01:12:24.990 --> 01:12:27.530
You won't get any interest,
because medicinal chemists have

01:12:27.530 --> 01:12:29.900
been burned too many
times, chasing ghosts--

01:12:29.900 --> 01:12:31.340
chasing artifacts.

01:12:31.340 --> 01:12:34.444
So we wanted to know, is this
a harbinger of a problem?

01:12:34.444 --> 01:12:35.860
Is there something
going on, here?

01:12:35.860 --> 01:12:39.410
Because DNA polymerases don't
recognize things like this.

01:12:39.410 --> 01:12:41.010
So how is it that--
I just told you

01:12:41.010 --> 01:12:42.810
that it's really
well replicated.

01:12:42.810 --> 01:12:43.350
How is that?

01:12:43.350 --> 01:12:44.183
This makes no sense.

01:12:44.183 --> 01:12:45.900
So let me tell you
what I mean by that.

01:12:45.900 --> 01:12:47.760
Here's a G-C base pair.

01:12:47.760 --> 01:12:50.880
G paired with C. Doesn't
matter whether it's in a duplex

01:12:50.880 --> 01:12:55.390
or whether it's at a
polymerase-active site, where

01:12:55.390 --> 01:12:57.390
you're pairing a triphosphate
against a template

01:12:57.390 --> 01:12:58.460
during synthesis.

01:12:58.460 --> 01:12:59.600
It just looks the same.

01:12:59.600 --> 01:13:01.262
A G-C looks the
same as a C-G. It

01:13:01.262 --> 01:13:03.720
looks the same as a T-A and an
A-T. They all look the same.

01:13:03.720 --> 01:13:05.345
The famous Watson-Crick
base-structure.

01:13:05.345 --> 01:13:06.449
There it is.

01:13:06.449 --> 01:13:07.740
That's not what ours look like.

01:13:07.740 --> 01:13:09.580
Ours are this weird
intercalation.

01:13:09.580 --> 01:13:11.484
Ours look more like
an A-A mis-pair.

01:13:11.484 --> 01:13:12.900
And how is it that
the polymerases

01:13:12.900 --> 01:13:13.910
are recognizing them?

01:13:13.910 --> 01:13:15.330
So this is how polymerases work.

01:13:15.330 --> 01:13:16.860
Polymerases look
like a right hand.

01:13:16.860 --> 01:13:20.480
The template lies down like
this-- in the palm domain.

01:13:20.480 --> 01:13:22.750
And when the correct
triphosphate binds,

01:13:22.750 --> 01:13:24.450
it induces a large
conformational change

01:13:24.450 --> 01:13:27.740
of the fingers domain, down
over the palm and thumb domains.

01:13:27.740 --> 01:13:29.750
That forms a tight
complex that's

01:13:29.750 --> 01:13:32.880
supposed to rigorously select
for a Watson-Crick base-pair

01:13:32.880 --> 01:13:33.601
structure.

01:13:33.601 --> 01:13:34.600
So we had two questions.

01:13:37.182 --> 01:13:39.640
Number one, does formation of
our unnatural base pair cause

01:13:39.640 --> 01:13:40.973
that same conformational change?

01:13:40.973 --> 01:13:43.956
Number two, if it does,
what is that closed complex

01:13:43.956 --> 01:13:44.455
recognizing?

01:13:44.455 --> 01:13:46.039
Because our pair
doesn't look anything

01:13:46.039 --> 01:13:47.079
like a Watson-Crick pair.

01:13:47.079 --> 01:13:49.350
It looks like a mis-pair the
polymerases were supposed

01:13:49.350 --> 01:13:50.615
to have evolved to avoid.

01:13:50.615 --> 01:13:52.990
So we collaborated with a good
friend of mine, Andy Marx,

01:13:52.990 --> 01:13:54.310
at the University
Konstanz, who solved

01:13:54.310 --> 01:13:55.330
a bunch of crystal structures.

01:13:55.330 --> 01:13:57.470
I'm willing to show a couple
of the key ones, here.

01:13:57.470 --> 01:14:00.759
This is the polymerase,
bound to the primer template.

01:14:00.759 --> 01:14:03.050
Here's the only part of the
polymerase I'm showing you.

01:14:03.050 --> 01:14:06.060
There are two helices at the
base of that fingers domain

01:14:06.060 --> 01:14:07.990
that I mentioned.

01:14:07.990 --> 01:14:09.490
And here's our
unnatural nucleotide,

01:14:09.490 --> 01:14:11.060
flipped out of the
developing duplex.

01:14:11.060 --> 01:14:11.910
Not a big surprise.

01:14:11.910 --> 01:14:14.120
Most of the natural
nucleobases do the same thing.

01:14:14.120 --> 01:14:16.120
There's a little hydrophobic
pocket right there.

01:14:16.120 --> 01:14:18.820
When you add the cognate
unnatural triphosphate,

01:14:18.820 --> 01:14:20.380
it flips back in.

01:14:20.380 --> 01:14:22.170
And you get a large
conformational change

01:14:22.170 --> 01:14:23.297
of that fingers domain.

01:14:23.297 --> 01:14:25.130
And, to show you that
conformational change,

01:14:25.130 --> 01:14:26.760
here's an overlay of
those two structures.

01:14:26.760 --> 01:14:28.170
And you can see the
conformational change,

01:14:28.170 --> 01:14:28.800
right there.

01:14:28.800 --> 01:14:30.640
To convince you it's
exactly the same

01:14:30.640 --> 01:14:33.190
as the conformational change
induced by a natural base pair,

01:14:33.190 --> 01:14:35.700
here's an overlay of those
complexes synthesizing

01:14:35.700 --> 01:14:37.820
our unnatural base pair
with that synthesizing

01:14:37.820 --> 01:14:40.660
a G-C. They're absolutely
superimposable,

01:14:40.660 --> 01:14:43.320
at the secondary structure-- the
protein-structure level-- even

01:14:43.320 --> 01:14:45.940
at the side-chain level,
and even at the bound water

01:14:45.940 --> 01:14:47.330
and magnesium level.

01:14:47.330 --> 01:14:49.860
So it really induces the very
same conformational change

01:14:49.860 --> 01:14:51.050
in the DNA polymerase.

01:14:51.050 --> 01:14:52.674
So now, what about
the second question?

01:14:52.674 --> 01:14:54.440
What's that closed
complex recognizing?

01:14:54.440 --> 01:14:57.170
And if your eyes are
good, you can already see.

01:14:57.170 --> 01:14:59.300
But if your eyes are like
mine, let me help you.

01:15:02.160 --> 01:15:04.774
This was a good day in my lab.

01:15:04.774 --> 01:15:06.440
The unnatural base
pair's not replicated

01:15:06.440 --> 01:15:07.880
by some weird mechanism.

01:15:07.880 --> 01:15:11.320
It's replicated by a subtle
variation of the same mechanism

01:15:11.320 --> 01:15:12.820
that a natural
pair's replicated by.

01:15:12.820 --> 01:15:15.830
A natural pair is replicated by
what's called an "induced fit

01:15:15.830 --> 01:15:17.430
mechanism," where
its formation drives

01:15:17.430 --> 01:15:18.930
a large conformational
change in the polymerase.

01:15:18.930 --> 01:15:20.039
I already mentioned that.

01:15:20.039 --> 01:15:21.580
The unnatural base
pair is replicated

01:15:21.580 --> 01:15:23.650
by a mutual induced
fit mechanism, where

01:15:23.650 --> 01:15:25.858
its formation drives that
large conformational change

01:15:25.858 --> 01:15:27.910
on the polymerase, but
that conformational change

01:15:27.910 --> 01:15:29.910
on the polymerase drives
a conformational change

01:15:29.910 --> 01:15:32.650
of the base pair,
to produce the pair

01:15:32.650 --> 01:15:34.870
that it needs for recognition.

01:15:34.870 --> 01:15:36.930
And I think the
ability to do this

01:15:36.930 --> 01:15:39.340
is exactly what we spent
12 years optimizing on

01:15:39.340 --> 01:15:40.987
in that med-chem-like campaign.

01:15:40.987 --> 01:15:43.570
I don't think-- if we would have
chosen any other force, other

01:15:43.570 --> 01:15:44.986
than hydrophobicity,
I don't think

01:15:44.986 --> 01:15:48.944
we would have had this
strength and flexibility

01:15:48.944 --> 01:15:49.860
to be able to do this.

01:15:49.860 --> 01:15:51.880
Because the hydrophobic
force is strong,

01:15:51.880 --> 01:15:53.230
but it's not very directional.

01:15:53.230 --> 01:15:57.350
So has the ability to respond to
the environment that it needs.

01:15:57.350 --> 01:15:59.510
So, having shown you
that replicates well,

01:15:59.510 --> 01:16:02.330
and actually believing that
we understood why-- we're not

01:16:02.330 --> 01:16:04.270
getting faked out, we're
not chasing a ghost--

01:16:04.270 --> 01:16:06.450
we sort of return to
our idea of trying

01:16:06.450 --> 01:16:08.490
to develop a semisynthetic
organism-- trying

01:16:08.490 --> 01:16:11.720
to implement the unnatural
base pair in a living cell.

01:16:11.720 --> 01:16:14.262
So the first problem that
just jumps out at you

01:16:14.262 --> 01:16:16.220
is, how do you get the
triphosphates available?

01:16:16.220 --> 01:16:18.199
So anyone who thinks
about nucleotide chemistry

01:16:18.199 --> 01:16:20.240
knows there's a couple
things that you could try.

01:16:20.240 --> 01:16:22.670
There are several drugs
based on free nucleosides

01:16:22.670 --> 01:16:25.660
defusing in through membranes
and then being metabolized up

01:16:25.660 --> 01:16:27.757
to this triphosphate
level by enzymes that

01:16:27.757 --> 01:16:28.965
are called "salvage" enzymes.

01:16:31.931 --> 01:16:34.190
It's one of the ways
cells make triphosphates.

01:16:34.190 --> 01:16:35.800
Bacteria do this
very sporadically.

01:16:35.800 --> 01:16:37.640
They don't actually
rely on it very much.

01:16:37.640 --> 01:16:39.617
And very little was
known about penetration

01:16:39.617 --> 01:16:40.450
across the membrane.

01:16:40.450 --> 01:16:44.400
Suffice it to say, despite
immense amount of work--

01:16:44.400 --> 01:16:46.670
about a year of work-- that
did not work, in my lab.

01:16:46.670 --> 01:16:47.680
We could not get that to work.

01:16:47.680 --> 01:16:48.930
So there's another
method that I'm not

01:16:48.930 --> 01:16:50.138
going to tell you much about.

01:16:50.138 --> 01:16:52.345
But you could imagine
protecting the-- I mean,

01:16:52.345 --> 01:16:54.470
the reason the triphosphates
won't get in-- they'll

01:16:54.470 --> 01:16:55.890
get into through
the outer membrane--

01:16:55.890 --> 01:16:57.760
this is a gram-negative--
this is an E. coli

01:16:57.760 --> 01:17:00.854
cell-- through channels
called "porins."

01:17:00.854 --> 01:17:02.270
They're just these
water channels.

01:17:02.270 --> 01:17:04.629
And this hydrophilic is
charged, so it'll diffuse in.

01:17:04.629 --> 01:17:07.170
But then it won't be able to
get across this inner membrane--

01:17:07.170 --> 01:17:09.740
Which, in this example, is blue.

01:17:09.740 --> 01:17:10.990
You might have not known that.

01:17:10.990 --> 01:17:15.457
The cytoplasmic membrane
of a gram-negative is blue.

01:17:15.457 --> 01:17:16.790
And so the charge prevents that.

01:17:16.790 --> 01:17:19.530
So maybe if you put on these
ester-blocking groups that

01:17:19.530 --> 01:17:22.110
oblate the charge, it'd
help them diffuse in.

01:17:22.110 --> 01:17:25.610
And then, once in,
maybe E. coli will

01:17:25.610 --> 01:17:28.330
have these nonspecific esterases
that-- just chop them off,

01:17:28.330 --> 01:17:29.630
and you're ready to go.

01:17:29.630 --> 01:17:30.190
Doesn't work.

01:17:30.190 --> 01:17:32.400
We made 18 analogs like that.

01:17:32.400 --> 01:17:33.620
And none of them would work.

01:17:33.620 --> 01:17:37.300
So we were really stuck,
not knowing what to do.

01:17:37.300 --> 01:17:39.340
This is where I
real-- so I just gave

01:17:39.340 --> 01:17:42.150
a talk to the graduate students
at Scripps, at a retreat.

01:17:42.150 --> 01:17:43.780
And the whole theme
of my talk was

01:17:43.780 --> 01:17:46.987
to think differently, in a
really interdisciplinary way.

01:17:46.987 --> 01:17:50.550
And this was the example I used.

01:17:50.550 --> 01:17:52.305
It turns out that
there are a variety

01:17:52.305 --> 01:17:55.820
of genomes that have this
really interesting property.

01:17:55.820 --> 01:17:58.817
And the property is, they
autonomously replicate.

01:17:58.817 --> 01:18:00.275
So they have to
have triphosphates,

01:18:00.275 --> 01:18:02.870
and-- but they don't
encode the machinery

01:18:02.870 --> 01:18:04.640
of triphosphate synthesis.

01:18:04.640 --> 01:18:08.230
And these genomes are some
obligate intracellular

01:18:08.230 --> 01:18:10.000
bacteria-- some
chlamydial species--

01:18:10.000 --> 01:18:15.550
and some plastids in
eukaryotes-- like algae.

01:18:15.550 --> 01:18:18.824
So, like mitochondria
and chloroplasts.

01:18:18.824 --> 01:18:20.990
What they do is-- I mean,
they live their whole life

01:18:20.990 --> 01:18:24.270
inside other cells, bathing in
the nutrients of those cells.

01:18:24.270 --> 01:18:26.021
So what they do is
they scavenge instead--

01:18:26.021 --> 01:18:27.686
they've just found
it easier to do that.

01:18:27.686 --> 01:18:29.710
Over evolutionary time,
they've optimized that.

01:18:29.710 --> 01:18:34.205
So what these
organisms do is they

01:18:34.205 --> 01:18:36.330
don't make the machinery
of triphosphate synthesis.

01:18:36.330 --> 01:18:38.246
What they do is they
make dedicated nucleoside

01:18:38.246 --> 01:18:41.390
triphosphate transporters
that assemble in the membrane

01:18:41.390 --> 01:18:44.280
and transport the triphosphates,
intact, as triphosphates,

01:18:44.280 --> 01:18:45.390
into the cell.

01:18:45.390 --> 01:18:49.250
We wrote all across the world
to about 18 different groups.

01:18:49.250 --> 01:18:53.570
And a few of them were
willing to send us their DNA.

01:18:53.570 --> 01:18:55.480
And so we cloned them
into our E. coli strain

01:18:55.480 --> 01:18:57.250
and asked if they would work.

01:18:57.250 --> 01:19:01.300
And they did, and we narrowed
it down to three or four.

01:19:01.300 --> 01:19:02.760
So this is the strategy.

01:19:02.760 --> 01:19:04.712
Because we found
that the idea would

01:19:04.712 --> 01:19:06.670
be to get a transporter
here, the triphosphates

01:19:06.670 --> 01:19:08.360
would diffuse in
through those porins

01:19:08.360 --> 01:19:11.750
and then get into the cytoplasm
through this transporter.

01:19:11.750 --> 01:19:14.475
And this particular transporter,
from a chlamydial species-- oh,

01:19:14.475 --> 01:19:16.230
I forgot to add a title.

01:19:16.230 --> 01:19:18.450
At least you know I got
this talk ready specifically

01:19:18.450 --> 01:19:18.991
for you guys.

01:19:21.290 --> 01:19:28.260
The transporter that we call
"PTNTT2"-- here's its activity.

01:19:28.260 --> 01:19:30.770
So it's importing A.
So what we're using

01:19:30.770 --> 01:19:32.670
is a radio-labeled
A triphosphate.

01:19:32.670 --> 01:19:34.930
So this is the triphosphate.

01:19:34.930 --> 01:19:36.790
This is the diphosphate,
meaning it's

01:19:36.790 --> 01:19:38.230
lost one of its phosphates.

01:19:38.230 --> 01:19:40.830
This is the monophosphate,
meaning it's lost two of them.

01:19:40.830 --> 01:19:45.020
And the product of removing
all three phosphates

01:19:45.020 --> 01:19:47.070
of the free nucleoside,
you just can't see,

01:19:47.070 --> 01:19:48.940
because the radio label's gone.

01:19:48.940 --> 01:19:51.680
But what we were
extremely excited to see

01:19:51.680 --> 01:19:53.610
was that it also
imported in the cytoplasm

01:19:53.610 --> 01:19:55.460
the triphosphates
of our analogs.

01:19:55.460 --> 01:19:58.541
And they decompose,
just like the ATP does.

01:19:58.541 --> 01:20:00.290
There's the triphosphate,
there's the di-,

01:20:00.290 --> 01:20:01.040
there's the mono-.

01:20:01.040 --> 01:20:02.830
Now we can see the
free nucleosides,

01:20:02.830 --> 01:20:05.970
because these are HPLC assays,
and we're not relying on radio

01:20:05.970 --> 01:20:06.764
labelling.

01:20:06.764 --> 01:20:09.180
So you can say, OK, there's a
lot of decomposition, there.

01:20:09.180 --> 01:20:09.920
And there is.

01:20:09.920 --> 01:20:11.350
And we're working
on solving that.

01:20:11.350 --> 01:20:14.480
We're tracking down what the
offending phosphatases are,

01:20:14.480 --> 01:20:16.770
and we think we've
finally found it.

01:20:16.770 --> 01:20:17.800
And we'll delete them.

01:20:17.800 --> 01:20:19.977
But what we noticed, about
a year ago or so-- a year

01:20:19.977 --> 01:20:21.560
and a half ago, god
knows-- two years,

01:20:21.560 --> 01:20:23.730
or something-- when we
were doing this work

01:20:23.730 --> 01:20:26.360
was that, even though these
concentrations were less

01:20:26.360 --> 01:20:31.770
than these, these were
30 and 50 micromolar.

01:20:31.770 --> 01:20:33.790
That's an order of
magnitude above the km

01:20:33.790 --> 01:20:36.830
for the polymerase, suggesting
that these concentrations

01:20:36.830 --> 01:20:37.940
should be sufficient.

01:20:37.940 --> 01:20:39.900
There should be enough
triphosphate in the cell

01:20:39.900 --> 01:20:40.250
to work.

01:20:40.250 --> 01:20:41.666
And these are
steady state levels.

01:20:41.666 --> 01:20:43.660
These are
concentrations that are

01:20:43.660 --> 01:20:46.800
the balance between the
importer pumping them in

01:20:46.800 --> 01:20:49.030
and the phosphatases
chewing them up.

01:20:49.030 --> 01:20:51.070
So we construct a
couple plasmid packs.

01:20:51.070 --> 01:20:52.550
It's the accessory
plasmids, where

01:20:52.550 --> 01:20:55.100
we plan on putting all the
accessories that we need

01:20:55.100 --> 01:20:56.630
for a semisynthetic organism.

01:20:56.630 --> 01:20:59.276
Right now, that's
just the transporter.

01:20:59.276 --> 01:21:01.150
And then what we call
"pINF," for information

01:21:01.150 --> 01:21:04.620
plasmid.And it's just
pUC-- just pUC19.

01:21:04.620 --> 01:21:06.800
The one difference
between pINF and pUC19

01:21:06.800 --> 01:21:10.500
is we replaced an
A-T pair with an X-Y.

01:21:10.500 --> 01:21:13.527
Now the X-Y was TPT3 dNAM.

01:21:13.527 --> 01:21:14.110
Remember this?

01:21:14.110 --> 01:21:16.630
This I told you replicated a
little bit better than this.

01:21:16.630 --> 01:21:19.960
So when we constructed
this plasmid synthetically,

01:21:19.960 --> 01:21:24.390
at our bench, we incorporated
this unnatural base pair.

01:21:24.390 --> 01:21:26.580
The experiment that
we're going to do

01:21:26.580 --> 01:21:27.956
is with this
unnatural base pair.

01:21:27.956 --> 01:21:29.800
And I'll tell you why
we did that a second.

01:21:29.800 --> 01:21:37.080
So the experiment is, transform
E. coli with this plasmid

01:21:37.080 --> 01:21:38.500
and induce
transporter production

01:21:38.500 --> 01:21:40.820
so they're competent to
take up the triphosphates.

01:21:40.820 --> 01:21:42.140
Then add the triphosphates.

01:21:45.100 --> 01:21:50.150
So transform and induce the
production of the transporter.

01:21:50.150 --> 01:21:52.790
Then add the requisite
unnatural triphosphates.

01:21:52.790 --> 01:21:55.380
And then add the unnatural
plasmid containing

01:21:55.380 --> 01:21:56.990
the unnatural base pair.

01:21:56.990 --> 01:21:59.390
And then recover that
plasmid as a function of time

01:21:59.390 --> 01:22:00.650
and characterize it.

01:22:00.650 --> 01:22:02.470
So there's a couple
control experiments

01:22:02.470 --> 01:22:03.344
that we wanted to do.

01:22:03.344 --> 01:22:05.080
We wanted to transform
with just pUC19,

01:22:05.080 --> 01:22:07.538
so it doesn't have the unnatural
base pair in the template.

01:22:07.538 --> 01:22:09.400
So if we're mis-inserting
the triphosphate,

01:22:09.400 --> 01:22:13.000
somehow, that's a
control against that.

01:22:13.000 --> 01:22:16.390
Or don't induce the
transporter, or don't add

01:22:16.390 --> 01:22:17.760
the unnatural triphosphates.

01:22:17.760 --> 01:22:20.280
So we recovered the
unnatural plasmid.

01:22:20.280 --> 01:22:22.910
We PCR-amplified the region
around the unnatural base pair.

01:22:22.910 --> 01:22:26.480
And when we PCR-amplified it,
we incorporated a biotin tag

01:22:26.480 --> 01:22:28.350
on one of the
unnatural nucleotides.

01:22:28.350 --> 01:22:30.480
And then we looked at a
streptavidin gel shift.

01:22:30.480 --> 01:22:33.340
So any place that retained
the unnatural base pair

01:22:33.340 --> 01:22:36.060
would then add this tag to it.

01:22:36.060 --> 01:22:39.100
And this tag resulted
in a gel shift.

01:22:39.100 --> 01:22:42.175
So in the controls where you
don't have the unnatural base

01:22:42.175 --> 01:22:44.272
pair in the template, you
never get a gel shift.

01:22:44.272 --> 01:22:46.480
When you have the unnatural
base pair in the template

01:22:46.480 --> 01:22:48.580
but you don't add the
requisite triphosphates,

01:22:48.580 --> 01:22:49.490
you get no shift.

01:22:49.490 --> 01:22:51.840
When you have the unnatural
base pair in the template,

01:22:51.840 --> 01:22:53.570
and you induce the
triphosphate, but you

01:22:53.570 --> 01:22:56.160
don't provide for their
uptake, you don't get a shift.

01:22:56.160 --> 01:22:58.730
Only when you have the unnatural
base pair in the template,

01:22:58.730 --> 01:23:01.150
provide the triphosphates,
and provide for their uptake

01:23:01.150 --> 01:23:04.241
do you get the shift.

01:23:04.241 --> 01:23:06.240
The same trick that I
showed you for sequencing,

01:23:06.240 --> 01:23:07.990
earlier, I don't know
if you can see this,

01:23:07.990 --> 01:23:11.590
but here's just standard
sequencing chromatograms.

01:23:11.590 --> 01:23:13.240
Suffice it to say
they look normal.

01:23:13.240 --> 01:23:14.970
And then only in the
experiment will you

01:23:14.970 --> 01:23:17.470
get the abrupt termination at
the site of the unnatural base

01:23:17.470 --> 01:23:17.600
pair.

01:23:17.600 --> 01:23:18.900
So we were pretty excited.

01:23:18.900 --> 01:23:22.110
We submitted this as a paper.

01:23:22.110 --> 01:23:24.310
Two of the three
reviewers agreed with us.

01:23:24.310 --> 01:23:27.060
One of the reviewers
didn't like two things.

01:23:27.060 --> 01:23:28.980
The reviewer didn't
like this step,

01:23:28.980 --> 01:23:30.610
and the reviewer
didn't like this step.

01:23:30.610 --> 01:23:33.500
He didn't like the fact that
we were manipulating the DNA

01:23:33.500 --> 01:23:35.030
after we got it out of a cell.

01:23:35.030 --> 01:23:37.400
So we collaborated
with NEB, which

01:23:37.400 --> 01:23:38.850
was a great collaboration.

01:23:38.850 --> 01:23:42.110
They have this
beautiful assay where

01:23:42.110 --> 01:23:44.577
they take an entire plasmid.

01:23:44.577 --> 01:23:46.660
So we'd just recover the
plasmid-- send it to NEB.

01:23:46.660 --> 01:23:50.670
They chop it up into
nucleosides and then analyze it

01:23:50.670 --> 01:23:52.021
by something called "LC-MS/MS."

01:23:52.021 --> 01:23:54.270
It's something that just
separates the nucleotides out

01:23:54.270 --> 01:23:56.890
and then uses something called
"mass spectrometry" to identify

01:23:56.890 --> 01:23:57.540
them.

01:23:57.540 --> 01:24:00.209
Here is the total C
content of the plasmid,

01:24:00.209 --> 01:24:02.500
the total G content of the
plasmid, the total A content

01:24:02.500 --> 01:24:03.330
of the plasmid.

01:24:03.330 --> 01:24:04.237
D doesn't fly well.

01:24:04.237 --> 01:24:05.820
It doesn't behave
well in their assay.

01:24:05.820 --> 01:24:07.736
And so it was expected
to have a small signal.

01:24:07.736 --> 01:24:09.390
But way out here,
right where we knew

01:24:09.390 --> 01:24:12.300
it would come, based on
its LC properties, is 5,6.

01:24:12.300 --> 01:24:15.340
And it's present
at one per genome.

01:24:15.340 --> 01:24:19.430
Now remember, the synthetic
plasmid that we made

01:24:19.430 --> 01:24:20.960
was with this.

01:24:20.960 --> 01:24:22.570
Was with TPT3.

01:24:22.570 --> 01:24:26.130
The only spot that
5,6 was provided

01:24:26.130 --> 01:24:29.840
was as a triphosphate
to the media.

01:24:29.840 --> 01:24:31.905
There was no detection of TPT3.

01:24:31.905 --> 01:24:32.990
It was only 5,6.

01:24:32.990 --> 01:24:34.510
So this is ambiguous
demonstration

01:24:34.510 --> 01:24:37.110
of replication of the unnatural
base pair inside the cell.

01:24:37.110 --> 01:24:40.990
Here is E. coli.

01:24:40.990 --> 01:24:43.230
Every organism since
the last common ancestor

01:24:43.230 --> 01:24:47.240
of all life on earth has had
two base pairs and four letters.

01:24:47.240 --> 01:24:51.180
These growing cells
have six and three.

01:24:51.180 --> 01:24:53.990
Very briefly, in the
remaining eight seconds--

01:24:53.990 --> 01:24:56.745
negative 8 seconds-- we're
continuing to look at analogs.

01:24:56.745 --> 01:24:58.870
We have a whole family of
replicable unnatural base

01:24:58.870 --> 01:24:59.370
pairs.

01:25:02.490 --> 01:25:05.340
Before, we had this transporter
encoded on a plasmid.

01:25:05.340 --> 01:25:07.770
We've now integrated
it into the chromosome.

01:25:07.770 --> 01:25:10.570
And, because found
out that it induced

01:25:10.570 --> 01:25:13.914
a little bit of toxicity
when we induced it,

01:25:13.914 --> 01:25:16.080
and that's why we had to
put on a high copy plasmid,

01:25:16.080 --> 01:25:18.730
so we didn't want any
selection pressure to lose it.

01:25:18.730 --> 01:25:21.050
We found all that toxicity
came from the N terminus.

01:25:21.050 --> 01:25:23.040
I mean, this is a
eukaryotic protein,

01:25:23.040 --> 01:25:29.230
so it had signals to guide it
through eukaryotic-specific

01:25:29.230 --> 01:25:32.247
parts of the cell that aren't
doing anything, in E. coli.

01:25:32.247 --> 01:25:34.330
You delete them, and the
cells are no longer sick.

01:25:34.330 --> 01:25:36.580
You can now put it behind
a constituent of promoter,

01:25:36.580 --> 01:25:39.407
so they're producing the
transporter all the time.

01:25:39.407 --> 01:25:41.990
They're always competent to take
up our natural triphosphates,

01:25:41.990 --> 01:25:45.950
and they grow with
wild type rates.

01:25:45.950 --> 01:25:49.560
So we've continued to move
on to the next step, now.

01:25:49.560 --> 01:25:51.120
And we're looking
at transcription.

01:25:51.120 --> 01:25:52.939
And this is all
relatively preliminary,

01:25:52.939 --> 01:25:54.730
but let me just finish
by saying we created

01:25:54.730 --> 01:25:56.854
another plasmid or this
time put the unnatural base

01:25:56.854 --> 01:25:59.010
pair in the gene.

01:25:59.010 --> 01:26:02.440
And this time we had to import
the ribo- and the deoxy- ribo

01:26:02.440 --> 01:26:06.300
variants of the unnatural
nucleotides, induce T7 RNA

01:26:06.300 --> 01:26:06.880
polymerase.

01:26:06.880 --> 01:26:09.066
So I didn't tell you,
but, during all that SAR,

01:26:09.066 --> 01:26:10.440
part of that
optimization effort,

01:26:10.440 --> 01:26:13.000
we also included recognition
by T7 RNA polymerase.

01:26:13.000 --> 01:26:15.250
So we wanted to make sure
that we had a base pair that

01:26:15.250 --> 01:26:18.510
was also transcribeable into
RNA so that it would produce

01:26:18.510 --> 01:26:19.680
the RNA and then analyze it.

01:26:19.680 --> 01:26:22.980
And so we isolated the RNA,
reverse-transcribing the PCR

01:26:22.980 --> 01:26:23.480
amplifier.

01:26:23.480 --> 01:26:25.646
So let me emphasize what
the unnatural base pair has

01:26:25.646 --> 01:26:27.730
to do to be detected here.

01:26:27.730 --> 01:26:29.850
The unnatural triphosphides
have to get in.

01:26:29.850 --> 01:26:32.835
It has to be stably
replicated within the plasmid.

01:26:32.835 --> 01:26:37.790
It has to be transcribed by
T7 DNA polymerase into RNA.

01:26:37.790 --> 01:26:40.080
It then has to survive
notoriously error-prone

01:26:40.080 --> 01:26:45.440
reverse transcription back into
DNA and then PCR amplification.

01:26:45.440 --> 01:26:46.940
And there it is.

01:26:46.940 --> 01:26:50.150
And we've done it now, in
about three different genes

01:26:50.150 --> 01:26:53.080
and a tRNA.

01:26:53.080 --> 01:26:56.969
And, with that, it remains
only to thank my group, which

01:26:56.969 --> 01:26:58.260
my current group is right here.

01:26:58.260 --> 01:27:02.830
And, of course, the New
England Biolabs group

01:27:02.830 --> 01:27:05.550
for that collaboration
was absolutely essential.

01:27:05.550 --> 01:27:07.050
And I mentioned
these collaborations

01:27:07.050 --> 01:27:09.860
for structural work and
these groups for funding.

01:27:09.860 --> 01:27:10.750
So, um, yeah.

01:27:10.750 --> 01:27:11.918
Thank you.

01:27:11.918 --> 01:27:14.792
[APPLAUSE]

01:27:19.590 --> 01:27:22.550
-Very, very, very cool
science, from all three

01:27:22.550 --> 01:27:24.560
of our fabulous speakers.

01:27:24.560 --> 01:27:28.550
The hour's late, but I think
we have time for questions,

01:27:28.550 --> 01:27:32.480
if people want to come
forward, up to the microphone,

01:27:32.480 --> 01:27:34.610
and please tell us
who you are, as you

01:27:34.610 --> 01:27:36.250
begin to ask your question.

01:27:38.850 --> 01:27:41.440
Please.

01:27:41.440 --> 01:27:42.930
-My name is Marcy Wells.

01:27:42.930 --> 01:27:48.610
And I have a question
about donor eggs.

01:27:48.610 --> 01:27:52.570
As I was watching your
presentations, instead

01:27:52.570 --> 01:27:54.830
of getting donor
eggs, can you just

01:27:54.830 --> 01:27:58.960
repair the mother's
eggs by taking out

01:27:58.960 --> 01:28:01.090
the damaged mitochondria?

01:28:03.610 --> 01:28:06.670
-There is a suggestion that
