01:28:11.110 --> 01:28:12.910
It's not proven.

01:28:12.910 --> 01:28:14.974
The problem we have--
in the UK, anyway--

01:28:14.974 --> 01:28:16.640
is that we would not
be allowed to do it

01:28:16.640 --> 01:28:19.610
because that would actually
probably be altering a genome.

01:28:19.610 --> 01:28:22.300
While it might be considered
legal, it's altering a genome.

01:28:22.300 --> 01:28:24.390
And we're not
allowed to do that.

01:28:24.390 --> 01:28:26.850
We're allowed to replace
the mitochondria.

01:28:26.850 --> 01:28:28.764
We're not allowed
to alter any genome.

01:28:32.070 --> 01:28:33.620
-Sir.

01:28:33.620 --> 01:28:36.540
-Irwin Shapiro,
astrophysicist at Harvard.

01:28:36.540 --> 01:28:38.570
I have a question for Floyd.

01:28:38.570 --> 01:28:42.250
Sort of a generic question.

01:28:42.250 --> 01:28:45.970
This is very fascinating
work, making more pairs

01:28:45.970 --> 01:28:47.789
from the conventional two pairs.

01:28:47.789 --> 01:28:50.205
-Yeah, everyone always told
me I should grow-- never mind.

01:28:50.205 --> 01:28:51.150
[LAUGHTER]

01:28:51.150 --> 01:28:51.966
-Sorry?

01:28:51.966 --> 01:28:53.590
-I was going to make
a joke, but then I

01:28:53.590 --> 01:28:57.080
pulled appropriately
back at the last second.

01:28:57.080 --> 01:29:02.650
-Do you have any speculations
as to why nature zeroed

01:29:02.650 --> 01:29:09.030
in on these two pairs-- A-T and
C-G-- as opposed to, say, three

01:29:09.030 --> 01:29:12.570
pairs or two other
pairs or whatever?

01:29:12.570 --> 01:29:14.060
-So I think it's
really difficult

01:29:14.060 --> 01:29:16.620
to ask those kind of
evolutionary questions.

01:29:16.620 --> 01:29:20.310
I think they're fascinating, but
they're difficult to disprove.

01:29:20.310 --> 01:29:23.820
So it's tough science.

01:29:23.820 --> 01:29:25.390
Let me mention a couple things.

01:29:25.390 --> 01:29:26.010
-Speculations.

01:29:26.010 --> 01:29:27.005
-Speculations-- sure.

01:29:27.005 --> 01:29:28.130
And I'm happy to speculate.

01:29:28.130 --> 01:29:31.150
But let me mention something
bout our unnatural base pair.

01:29:31.150 --> 01:29:33.990
We need the natural
environment provided by C-G

01:29:33.990 --> 01:29:36.390
and A-T. We could
never make long

01:29:36.390 --> 01:29:40.754
stretches-- we could replicate
long stretches of just X and Y.

01:29:40.754 --> 01:29:41.920
Of course, we don't need to.

01:29:41.920 --> 01:29:44.200
All we want to do
is evolve proteins

01:29:44.200 --> 01:29:45.790
with multiple
unnatural amino acids,

01:29:45.790 --> 01:29:47.380
and you would never
need stretches.

01:29:47.380 --> 01:29:52.460
I mean, if you only could
incorporate one base pair,

01:29:52.460 --> 01:29:56.527
there's more codons
than we could ever use.

01:29:56.527 --> 01:29:59.110
I think that, you know, that's
a question that a lot of people

01:29:59.110 --> 01:29:59.900
have asked.

01:29:59.900 --> 01:30:02.700
Watson very famously called
it a "frozen accident."

01:30:02.700 --> 01:30:07.520
I tend to sort of think that
that's probably right, in that,

01:30:07.520 --> 01:30:10.040
for whatever reason, it
happened across G-C and A-T--

01:30:10.040 --> 01:30:12.010
probably because they
were available, somehow,

01:30:12.010 --> 01:30:13.843
in whatever the environment
was at the time.

01:30:13.843 --> 01:30:15.690
And they worked good enough.

01:30:15.690 --> 01:30:18.700
So, no more selection pressure.

01:30:18.700 --> 01:30:22.550
I think all that my work does
is suggest that maybe they

01:30:22.550 --> 01:30:25.646
could've done more if
they had wanted to.

01:30:25.646 --> 01:30:28.860
-[LAUGH]

01:30:28.860 --> 01:30:31.010
-I'll add a question to that.

01:30:31.010 --> 01:30:33.960
Given that we can
only sequence DNA

01:30:33.960 --> 01:30:38.910
with the way we can
sequence it, how do we know?

01:30:38.910 --> 01:30:41.180
-I actually get that
question sometimes.

01:30:41.180 --> 01:30:42.768
-[LAUGH] You just did.

01:30:42.768 --> 01:30:45.010
[LAUGHTER]

01:30:45.010 --> 01:30:46.200
-Good question.

01:30:46.200 --> 01:30:47.830
I mean, I think
it's very unlikely

01:30:47.830 --> 01:30:50.800
that there's anything as
radically different as NAM

01:30:50.800 --> 01:30:51.910
and 5,6.

01:30:51.910 --> 01:30:52.795
But-- sure.

01:30:52.795 --> 01:30:53.670
-[INAUDIBLE] we know.

01:30:53.670 --> 01:30:55.530
-Sure.

01:30:55.530 --> 01:30:56.030
-Sir.

01:30:56.030 --> 01:30:56.529
-Hi.

01:30:56.529 --> 01:30:59.300
I'm Ryan Cross, from the Boston
University Science Journalism

01:30:59.300 --> 01:30:59.800
program.

01:30:59.800 --> 01:31:02.060
This is a question for Dr. Corn.

01:31:02.060 --> 01:31:07.380
Could you speak a little bit
about the non-GMO gene editing

01:31:07.380 --> 01:31:10.230
trend that's going on
in biotech right now?

01:31:10.230 --> 01:31:13.040
Specifically with
editing plant genomes.

01:31:13.040 --> 01:31:15.250
Scientists seem to
have a lot of buzz

01:31:15.250 --> 01:31:19.060
about using CRISPR Cas to
navigate around current GMO

01:31:19.060 --> 01:31:20.788
regulations.

01:31:20.788 --> 01:31:21.779
-Oh.

01:31:21.779 --> 01:31:23.320
I mean, I think what
you're referring

01:31:23.320 --> 01:31:27.040
to is the current definition
of GMO is that there's

01:31:27.040 --> 01:31:28.460
a selection marker in there.

01:31:28.460 --> 01:31:30.350
And one of the
possibilities of Cas9

01:31:30.350 --> 01:31:33.120
is that you could do the editing
without introducing a selection

01:31:33.120 --> 01:31:33.990
marker.

01:31:33.990 --> 01:31:36.599
And therefore it would
not be technically GMO.

01:31:36.599 --> 01:31:38.140
Out of the companies
that I've talked

01:31:38.140 --> 01:31:39.960
to that are serious
players in this game,

01:31:39.960 --> 01:31:45.555
they think a lot about how would
their product be perceived.

01:31:45.555 --> 01:31:47.680
I don't know if they've
fully learned their lesson,

01:31:47.680 --> 01:31:50.104
but they've learned that
people pay attention

01:31:50.104 --> 01:31:51.020
to that sort of stuff.

01:31:51.020 --> 01:31:54.220
So I have not heard
anyone, so far,

01:31:54.220 --> 01:31:56.640
say we want to try
to slide something

01:31:56.640 --> 01:31:58.840
under the radar with this.

01:31:58.840 --> 01:32:03.130
And I've even heard at least
one of them say, oh, someone

01:32:03.130 --> 01:32:06.040
was mentioning this fact
to me and I berated them.

01:32:06.040 --> 01:32:08.780
So I think that
they, on that end,

01:32:08.780 --> 01:32:12.380
are not thinking about
doing something like that.

01:32:12.380 --> 01:32:14.490
If they were to try
to-- well, first off,

01:32:14.490 --> 01:32:22.565
I think they're going to
be more slow to adopt this

01:32:22.565 --> 01:32:24.940
in a commercial standpoint,
because they don't want to be

01:32:24.940 --> 01:32:26.066
the ones running out ahead.

01:32:26.066 --> 01:32:26.565
Right?

01:32:26.565 --> 01:32:28.300
They already know
that they're going

01:32:28.300 --> 01:32:31.160
to catch flak for that sort
of thing, deserved or not.

01:32:31.160 --> 01:32:33.659
And so they're going to wait,
and they're going to see.

01:32:33.659 --> 01:32:35.200
As to what startups
are going to do--

01:32:35.200 --> 01:32:38.450
you know, biofuel, algae,
things outside of what

01:32:38.450 --> 01:32:41.069
we might eat or
put in our mouths--

01:32:41.069 --> 01:32:42.110
that's a different thing.

01:32:42.110 --> 01:32:45.740
There is one guy who's
doing some interesting stuff

01:32:45.740 --> 01:32:47.230
with livestock.

01:32:47.230 --> 01:32:48.899
This is not with Cas9.

01:32:48.899 --> 01:32:49.940
This is Scott Fahrenkrug.

01:32:49.940 --> 01:32:53.900
He has a company called,
I think, Recombinetics.

01:32:53.900 --> 01:32:56.890
And it turns out that this is--

01:32:56.890 --> 01:32:59.740
For him, it's more
of a humane thing.

01:32:59.740 --> 01:33:02.780
So it turns out that,
in the US, dairy cattle

01:33:02.780 --> 01:33:04.200
are born with horns.

01:33:04.200 --> 01:33:06.130
And they have to be removed.

01:33:06.130 --> 01:33:08.381
And you can imagine that's
not a very nice process

01:33:08.381 --> 01:33:09.005
for the animal.

01:33:09.005 --> 01:33:11.850
So all dairy cattle in the
US have this done to them.

01:33:11.850 --> 01:33:14.190
Whether you knew that or
not, it's really nasty,

01:33:14.190 --> 01:33:15.250
and it's really terrible.

01:33:15.250 --> 01:33:17.180
And the videos that he
shows are really bad.

01:33:17.180 --> 01:33:19.970
But it turns out there's a
natural allele called "polled"

01:33:19.970 --> 01:33:22.150
that is naturally in
the cow population.

01:33:22.150 --> 01:33:23.900
And cows are just
not born with those.

01:33:23.900 --> 01:33:26.535
Well, the gestation time
with cows is very, very long.

01:33:26.535 --> 01:33:29.160
So if you try to introduce this
in all the various cow species,

01:33:29.160 --> 01:33:30.310
it would take forever.

01:33:30.310 --> 01:33:32.930
And so he's been able to
edit the naturally occurring

01:33:32.930 --> 01:33:35.654
polled mutation into a
variety of founder cows.

01:33:35.654 --> 01:33:38.070
And they're normal cows; they're
just not born with horns.

01:33:38.070 --> 01:33:39.810
You don't have to
cut them off anymore.

01:33:39.810 --> 01:33:42.350
And so the goal with
his company is more

01:33:42.350 --> 01:33:46.102
to not change the way we're
eating anything but to take

01:33:46.102 --> 01:33:47.810
a naturally observed
mutation and make it

01:33:47.810 --> 01:33:50.901
so we don't have to do
these inhumane things.

01:33:50.901 --> 01:33:51.883
-Thank you.

01:33:51.883 --> 01:33:53.356
-OK.

01:33:53.356 --> 01:33:54.070
-Hi.

01:33:54.070 --> 01:33:55.070
I'm Jennifer Hochschild.

01:33:55.070 --> 01:33:57.195
I'm a faculty member with
the Government department

01:33:57.195 --> 01:33:57.880
at Harvard.

01:33:57.880 --> 01:33:59.480
So I have a sort
of a meta meta meta

01:33:59.480 --> 01:34:01.435
question, which is probably
too late in the afternoon.

01:34:01.435 --> 01:34:03.700
And I don't know how anybody
could answer it, anyway.

01:34:03.700 --> 01:34:07.060
But what I'm struck
with is the contrast

01:34:07.060 --> 01:34:09.590
between the previous
lecture by Dr. Kaplan

01:34:09.590 --> 01:34:14.245
and the kind of enthusiasm,
excitement, recognition

01:34:14.245 --> 01:34:16.770
that there are deep moral,
ethical, political issues.

01:34:16.770 --> 01:34:19.380
I mean, you guys are all very
sophisticated about this.

01:34:19.380 --> 01:34:22.770
But his fundamental
concern is, how are we

01:34:22.770 --> 01:34:28.400
going to avoid seriously
harming people or society

01:34:28.400 --> 01:34:30.300
through these new techniques?

01:34:30.300 --> 01:34:33.030
Your positions,
collectively, are, look

01:34:33.030 --> 01:34:36.090
at all a fascinating, wonderful,
terrifically exciting things

01:34:36.090 --> 01:34:38.340
we can do to benefit
society through all

01:34:38.340 --> 01:34:40.316
these new techniques.

01:34:40.316 --> 01:34:41.940
Those aren't necessarily
contradictory,

01:34:41.940 --> 01:34:44.370
but they always tend in
different directions.

01:34:44.370 --> 01:34:45.620
How does one think about that?

01:34:45.620 --> 01:34:47.245
I mean, my instinct
is to say that this

01:34:47.245 --> 01:34:49.190
is sort of characterological.

01:34:49.190 --> 01:34:50.620
That some people
are more focused

01:34:50.620 --> 01:34:53.100
on avoiding harm and some
people are more focused

01:34:53.100 --> 01:34:54.980
on producing gains.

01:34:54.980 --> 01:34:56.660
But that's probably too simple.

01:34:56.660 --> 01:35:00.440
So is there any way to get
into that very big question

01:35:00.440 --> 01:35:04.810
of how do we frame these issues?

01:35:04.810 --> 01:35:07.720
-How about quick answers,
right down the row?

01:35:07.720 --> 01:35:09.458
-I'll leave it to them.

01:35:09.458 --> 01:35:13.665
[LAUGHTER]

01:35:13.665 --> 01:35:14.165
-Yeah.

01:35:14.165 --> 01:35:15.660
It's a big issue,
and it's an issue

01:35:15.660 --> 01:35:17.934
that I've faced throughout
my clinical practice.

01:35:17.934 --> 01:35:19.850
Because when you're
working as a gynecologist,

01:35:19.850 --> 01:35:23.219
you're working with all
these issues all the time.

01:35:23.219 --> 01:35:24.760
I would probably
only say two things.

01:35:24.760 --> 01:35:25.660
The first thing
is that you can't

01:35:25.660 --> 01:35:26.868
stop the progress of science.

01:35:26.868 --> 01:35:28.560
You can't stop people thinking.

01:35:28.560 --> 01:35:31.314
And if you make legislation
in one country that

01:35:31.314 --> 01:35:32.730
stops something
being done, you'll

01:35:32.730 --> 01:35:33.854
go through another country.

01:35:33.854 --> 01:35:35.720
That's the way it will happen.

01:35:35.720 --> 01:35:38.550
And that's human nature.

01:35:38.550 --> 01:35:40.229
The way we've done
it clinically--

01:35:40.229 --> 01:35:42.520
and I think there's a difference
between what you do it

01:35:42.520 --> 01:35:45.320
in the laboratory, in terms
of scientific understanding,

01:35:45.320 --> 01:35:47.400
and then introducing
it in the medical field

01:35:47.400 --> 01:35:50.795
into clinical practice in a
way that might-- hopefully help

01:35:50.795 --> 01:35:53.900
but theoretically
might harm people--

01:35:53.900 --> 01:35:57.850
is how you get
that balance right.

01:35:57.850 --> 01:35:59.990
I've always done things--
one, there's two things.

01:35:59.990 --> 01:36:01.690
Firstly, there's
a clinical need.

01:36:01.690 --> 01:36:03.560
So I've got patients
coming to me saying,

01:36:03.560 --> 01:36:07.400
there's a problem here we want
you to try and solve for us.

01:36:07.400 --> 01:36:10.890
And I have to listen to them,
because I'm a clinician.

01:36:10.890 --> 01:36:13.740
And then the other way is
to go about it in a way that

01:36:13.740 --> 01:36:15.150
takes the public along with it.

01:36:15.150 --> 01:36:16.410
And it's explaining to people.

01:36:16.410 --> 01:36:18.440
If you explain to them
what it is you're doing

01:36:18.440 --> 01:36:21.150
and why you're doing it, and
you do all the tests you can,

01:36:21.150 --> 01:36:24.070
they then start to see you're
not some sort of Frankenstein

01:36:24.070 --> 01:36:25.160
monsters.

01:36:25.160 --> 01:36:27.610
But people are just generally
trying to help people.

01:36:27.610 --> 01:36:32.150
And we've got a responsibility--
we've got an obligation

01:36:32.150 --> 01:36:36.687
to be responsible about it
and not to sit in ivory towers

01:36:36.687 --> 01:36:38.520
and play around with
things, but to actually

01:36:38.520 --> 01:36:40.480
just be open and explain
what we're doing.

01:36:40.480 --> 01:36:42.480
And in the sort of
stuff that I've been,

01:36:42.480 --> 01:36:45.310
there's always
been a good cause.

01:36:45.310 --> 01:36:49.340
-I think from the standpoint
of genome editing, as least,

01:36:49.340 --> 01:36:52.480
what I would stress is
these things are just tools.

01:36:52.480 --> 01:36:55.900
You can use a hammer
to hit someone with,

01:36:55.900 --> 01:36:57.310
but you can also build a house.

01:36:57.310 --> 01:36:59.900
It doesn't mean the hammer is
bad; it's what we do with it.

01:36:59.900 --> 01:37:01.770
And we have a choice
of what we do it.

01:37:01.770 --> 01:37:05.860
So I think that, you
know, you could say, well,

01:37:05.860 --> 01:37:07.110
let's not use hammers anymore.

01:37:07.110 --> 01:37:08.160
Well, you've still
got to build houses.

01:37:08.160 --> 01:37:09.950
Now you're building
houses with rocks.

01:37:09.950 --> 01:37:12.800
You're smashing nails
in-- stuff like that.

01:37:12.800 --> 01:37:15.610
So I think there's
been a lot of buzz

01:37:15.610 --> 01:37:17.617
around Cas9 and
germ-line editing,

01:37:17.617 --> 01:37:18.575
and that sort of thing.

01:37:18.575 --> 01:37:20.730
And it's really more about,
what do you do with it?

01:37:20.730 --> 01:37:20.950
Right?

01:37:20.950 --> 01:37:22.857
It's about the biologies
that you can learn.

01:37:22.857 --> 01:37:24.440
Maybe that just makes
me an optimist--

01:37:24.440 --> 01:37:26.314
that I think that there's
a lot we can learn,

01:37:26.314 --> 01:37:28.340
and there's a lot of
people that we can help.

01:37:28.340 --> 01:37:31.400
But it's not that the tool
has any inherent good.

01:37:31.400 --> 01:37:34.530
The good is in how you use it.

01:37:34.530 --> 01:37:37.810
-I would also add that all of
the work you've heard today

01:37:37.810 --> 01:37:42.600
is not done without considerable
oversight-- oversight

01:37:42.600 --> 01:37:46.060
from funding agencies,
oversight from the institutions

01:37:46.060 --> 01:37:48.850
that employ the
scientists, oversights

01:37:48.850 --> 01:37:51.600
from the national
institutes of health

01:37:51.600 --> 01:37:54.930
and other federal
regulatory elements.

01:37:54.930 --> 01:37:58.350
And I think that the
protections are there.

01:37:58.350 --> 01:37:59.980
They're not foolproof.

01:37:59.980 --> 01:38:04.520
And that's why getting
you, the population, who

01:38:04.520 --> 01:38:08.070
will potentially benefit
from this research,

01:38:08.070 --> 01:38:11.100
and hopefully not
harm, to understand

01:38:11.100 --> 01:38:14.850
the opportunity, the challenges,
and the ethics involved.

01:38:14.850 --> 01:38:16.350
You all need to be engaged.

01:38:16.350 --> 01:38:18.480
You've been fabulously
engage today.

01:38:18.480 --> 01:38:22.100
And at this point I'm going to
let Janet Rich-Edwards close us

01:38:22.100 --> 01:38:25.541
out today, because the hour's
late, and it's time for beer.

01:38:25.541 --> 01:38:26.965
[LAUGHTER]

01:38:26.965 --> 01:38:27.465
[APPLAUSE]

01:38:27.465 --> 01:38:30.360
-Well said!

01:38:30.360 --> 01:38:32.810
I do want to thank
all our speakers--

01:38:32.810 --> 01:38:35.910
this wonderful panel-- this
morning's panels and speakers--

01:38:35.910 --> 01:38:36.680
thank all of you.

01:38:36.680 --> 01:38:38.816
Thank our online audience.

01:38:38.816 --> 01:38:40.690
I've just been given
the list of where people

01:38:40.690 --> 01:38:41.940
have been logging in from.

01:38:41.940 --> 01:38:44.660
It is all over the US,
all over the world.

01:38:44.660 --> 01:38:47.690
Peru, Finland,
Kyrgyzstan, India.

01:38:47.690 --> 01:38:52.180
I think every continent is
represented except Australia.

01:38:52.180 --> 01:38:53.890
I've got to wonder
what's up with them.

01:38:53.890 --> 01:38:56.810
So it's my charge to just
summarize, really quickly.

01:38:56.810 --> 01:39:00.050
I've got to say, I
learned a lot today.

01:39:00.050 --> 01:39:01.770
I think we learned a
lot about discovery.

01:39:01.770 --> 01:39:04.480
You can feel the palpable
excitement, here.

01:39:04.480 --> 01:39:07.200
We learned a lot, this
morning, about our history.

01:39:07.200 --> 01:39:08.840
I learned that our
history as humans

01:39:08.840 --> 01:39:12.810
is more of a braided stream
than the old hard tree

01:39:12.810 --> 01:39:14.300
that I'd imagined.

01:39:14.300 --> 01:39:17.150
I learned that we are,
today, more genetically

01:39:17.150 --> 01:39:20.520
similar amongst ourselves
than even our ancestors were.

01:39:20.520 --> 01:39:24.192
We have talked about
fantastic advances in biology.

01:39:24.192 --> 01:39:25.900
There's all sorts of
stuff we didn't even

01:39:25.900 --> 01:39:30.430
talk about, like the fact
that all women are mosaics.

01:39:30.430 --> 01:39:32.270
We all have one of
our Xs turned off.

01:39:32.270 --> 01:39:35.987
Or that we're actually,
humans, chimeras.

01:39:35.987 --> 01:39:38.320
If you're a mother, you carry
the cells of your children

01:39:38.320 --> 01:39:39.153
in your bloodstream.

01:39:40.985 --> 01:39:42.360
If you're a twin,
you're carrying

01:39:42.360 --> 01:39:44.620
some your twin's cells.

01:39:44.620 --> 01:39:48.090
So there's actually things as
strange in our current biology

01:39:48.090 --> 01:39:50.900
that we're still learning about
through some of these new tools

01:39:50.900 --> 01:39:54.590
and some of these
fantastical future visions.

01:39:54.590 --> 01:39:56.900
We've learned about
prevention-- how

01:39:56.900 --> 01:40:00.020
we can prevent diseases,
such as the mitochondrial DNA

01:40:00.020 --> 01:40:01.380
techniques we've heard about.

01:40:01.380 --> 01:40:04.230
We've learned about
protection of innocent people,

01:40:04.230 --> 01:40:07.690
of endangered species, even
of languages and cultures

01:40:07.690 --> 01:40:09.100
we talked about this morning.

01:40:09.100 --> 01:40:11.720
We've talked about new
therapies on the horizon.

01:40:11.720 --> 01:40:14.520
The hematopoietic diseases,
those blood diseases,

01:40:14.520 --> 01:40:17.890
HIV-- can you
imagine curing HIV?

01:40:17.890 --> 01:40:18.570
--for ourselves.

01:40:18.570 --> 01:40:21.760
And we've even talked about
it a bit for other species.

01:40:21.760 --> 01:40:23.720
What could, for
example, mammoth DNA

01:40:23.720 --> 01:40:25.760
do to help the Asian elephant?

01:40:25.760 --> 01:40:30.620
We have a fantastic,
brand-new toolbox.

01:40:30.620 --> 01:40:34.360
We've talked about it as swords,
scalpels, knives, scissors.

01:40:34.360 --> 01:40:36.190
We are like three-year-olds,
running around

01:40:36.190 --> 01:40:37.440
with these tools in our hands.

01:40:37.440 --> 01:40:40.220
And I think there's
a lot of work

01:40:40.220 --> 01:40:43.730
to do-- all of us, not
just the scientists,

01:40:43.730 --> 01:40:45.800
not just the
regulators-- all of us,

01:40:45.800 --> 01:40:48.190
to consider where we
want to take this.

01:40:48.190 --> 01:40:50.650
I think one of the most
exciting things today

01:40:50.650 --> 01:40:53.427
is this talk of the
power of citizen science.

01:40:53.427 --> 01:40:55.510
We've talked about the
democratization of science,

01:40:55.510 --> 01:40:57.530
the fact that the barriers
for doing this stuff

01:40:57.530 --> 01:40:59.970
are coming way down.

01:40:59.970 --> 01:41:02.550
We didn't talk so
much about the dream

01:41:02.550 --> 01:41:05.344
or the spectre of garage labs.

01:41:05.344 --> 01:41:06.760
It's now getting
easier and easier

01:41:06.760 --> 01:41:10.150
to do this outside
of the institutions

01:41:10.150 --> 01:41:12.940
that we're used to
regulating things for us.

01:41:12.940 --> 01:41:15.450
We've talked about
needing to anticipate

01:41:15.450 --> 01:41:18.200
the ethical and legal
issues, the importance

01:41:18.200 --> 01:41:21.220
of public perception, and
the importance of using

01:41:21.220 --> 01:41:26.050
careful, precise language as
we describe what we're doing.

01:41:26.050 --> 01:41:28.410
Last, it occurred
to me today that we

01:41:28.410 --> 01:41:33.550
are the first species that
can edit its own evolution.

01:41:33.550 --> 01:41:36.350
This stuff is
incredibly profound.

01:41:36.350 --> 01:41:38.350
It could take us anywhere.

01:41:38.350 --> 01:41:40.350
And it's up to us to guide it.

01:41:40.350 --> 01:41:43.510
I just, uh-- what did we say?

01:41:43.510 --> 01:41:46.150
We can't stop progress, and
we can't stop people thinking.

01:41:46.150 --> 01:41:47.027
That's true.

01:41:47.027 --> 01:41:49.360
But I would just say let's
be sure that our intelligence

01:41:49.360 --> 01:41:51.360
doesn't outrun our wisdom.

01:41:51.360 --> 01:41:53.480
Thank you all very much
for a terrific day,

01:41:53.480 --> 01:41:55.300
and we'll see you soon.

01:41:55.300 --> 01:41:58.050
[APPLAUSE]

